1
00:03:17,254 --> 00:03:22,424
NARRATOR: This land has a name today
and is marked on maps.

2
00:03:22,592 --> 00:03:27,512
But the names and the marks and the land
all had to be won.

3
00:03:27,680 --> 00:03:31,140
Won from nature and from primitive man.

4
00:03:31,934 --> 00:03:37,438
Five generations ago,
a mere 125 years back...

5
00:03:37,606 --> 00:03:40,649
...this land was known
only as the West.

6
00:03:40,817 --> 00:03:44,194
Known only to a handful of white men...

7
00:03:44,362 --> 00:03:49,116
...lomely trappers wandering its vastness
in search of beaver.

8
00:03:49,284 --> 00:03:52,369
They were known as mountain men,
a mew breed.

9
00:03:52,537 --> 00:03:57,456
Men like Jim Bridger,
Franchère and Sublette, Linus Rawlings.

10
00:03:57,624 --> 00:04:01,043
More Indian than the Indians
in all but blood.

11
00:04:01,211 --> 00:04:04,171
They held to no law but their own...

12
00:04:04,339 --> 00:04:09,926
...drifted free as the clouds,
settled nowhere, kept forever on the move.

13
00:04:10,094 --> 00:04:15,932
Their moccasined feet and unshod horses
leaving no trace on the land.

14
00:04:17,310 --> 00:04:20,145
Like the Indians,
with whom they were at peace...

15
00:04:20,313 --> 00:04:24,815
...they wanted nothing beyond
what they found, and little of that.

16
00:04:25,483 --> 00:04:29,486
The mountains, the forests,
the harsh country...

17
00:04:29,654 --> 00:04:33,157
...were as unchanging to them
as the stars...

18
00:04:33,325 --> 00:04:36,035
...and just as unyielding.

19
00:04:37,621 --> 00:04:41,748
Far behind the mountains,
beyond the rolling plains...

20
00:04:41,916 --> 00:04:47,629
...they had left the people of the East,
people who were restless in another way.

21
00:04:48,339 --> 00:04:51,674
The kind who'd look at a mountain
and see a watershed...

22
00:04:51,842 --> 00:04:54,135
...look at a forest
and see lumber for houses...

23
00:04:54,303 --> 00:04:57,012
...look at a stony field and see a farm.

24
00:04:57,180 --> 00:05:01,266
Their faces and their instincts
had been turned to the West...

25
00:05:01,434 --> 00:05:04,519
...ever since Plymouth Rock
and Jamestown.

26
00:05:04,687 --> 00:05:08,774
The trapper's road was the trail
of a wolf or the bend of a canyon.

27
00:05:08,942 --> 00:05:12,443
But for whole families
chaffing to follow the sun...

28
00:05:12,611 --> 00:05:15,154
...there had to be broader ways.

29
00:05:15,322 --> 00:05:19,867
There were no roads into the wilderness,
only rivers.

30
00:05:20,035 --> 00:05:23,079
And they flowed in the wrong direction:
north or south.

31
00:05:23,246 --> 00:05:26,373
Or else they stopped at the Alleghenies.

32
00:05:26,791 --> 00:05:33,296
Until one day, a mew river took source
in the mind of a man named DeWitt Clinton.

33
00:05:33,756 --> 00:05:36,883
He conceived of a river
that would go west.

34
00:05:37,051 --> 00:05:42,388
And in the way Americans have
of acting out their dreams, it came to be.

35
00:05:42,555 --> 00:05:45,224
The Erie Canal left the Hudson
above Albany...

36
00:05:45,392 --> 00:05:48,852
...and carried clear across
to the Great Lakes.

37
00:05:49,229 --> 00:05:52,398
People who yearned for virgin land
and a mew life...

38
00:05:52,565 --> 00:05:54,899
...now had a highway to take them.

39
00:05:55,067 --> 00:05:56,651
And they moved along.

40
00:05:56,819 --> 00:05:59,404
MAN:
Pride of Utica now loading!

41
00:06:00,072 --> 00:06:03,783
Al aboard for the Pride of Utica!

42
00:06:03,951 --> 00:06:07,578
The Ramsey family, Peter Smith...

43
00:06:07,746 --> 00:06:10,122
...the Skoga family!

44
00:06:10,289 --> 00:06:12,290
All eight of then!

45
00:06:12,458 --> 00:06:17,004
Al aboard for the Pride of Utica!

46
00:06:18,423 --> 00:06:21,299
Is the laddie's health
the reason you're heading west?

47
00:06:21,467 --> 00:06:22,592
Partly.

48
00:06:22,760 --> 00:06:25,761
Only partly.
Mostly our trouble East was rocks.

49
00:06:25,929 --> 00:06:29,432
I had me a farm where some years I'd
raise 100 bushels of rocks to the acre.

50
00:06:29,599 --> 00:06:32,101
Zebulon, you hadn't
ought to lie to the nan like that.

51
00:06:32,269 --> 00:06:35,855
Wife, I'm a God-fearing soul,
and I tell the truth as I see it.

52
00:06:36,106 --> 00:06:39,442
Now, I never used a plow.
I'd blast out the furrows with gunpowder.

53
00:06:39,609 --> 00:06:42,527
And then one morning,
I hauled the bucket up out of the well...

54
00:06:42,695 --> 00:06:45,572
...and so help me,
the bucket was full of rocks.

55
00:06:45,740 --> 00:06:46,781
Rocks.

56
00:06:46,949 --> 00:06:50,076
I just stood there right still
trying not to blaspheme.

57
00:06:50,286 --> 00:06:52,662
I said to myself,
"You've got a son that's ailing...

58
00:06:52,830 --> 00:06:55,414
...you've got a daughter
what won't take to herself a husband."

59
00:06:55,582 --> 00:06:57,791
There she sits there, mooning as usual.
Pa.

60
00:06:57,959 --> 00:07:00,794
You've got another who don't seem
quite right in the head.

61
00:07:00,962 --> 00:07:02,963
Lilith?

62
00:07:04,758 --> 00:07:06,633
LILITH:
Yes. Pa?

63
00:07:07,802 --> 00:07:09,678
Now, I'll remind you. sir.

64
00:07:09,845 --> 00:07:13,806
I'm still standing there
holding a bucket full of rocks...

65
00:07:13,974 --> 00:07:16,851
...and staring into a bleak old age.

66
00:07:17,019 --> 00:07:19,395
So I made me a vow
right then and there. I said:

67
00:07:19,563 --> 00:07:23,816
"If I can find a man with $500
who likes rocks...

68
00:07:23,984 --> 00:07:26,651
...then there's gonna be another fool
owning this farm."

69
00:07:26,819 --> 00:07:30,489
Well, sir, the Lord provided such a nan...

70
00:07:30,656 --> 00:07:31,865
...and here I an.

71
00:07:32,033 --> 00:07:34,826
He ain't told you one word of truth,
Mr. Harvey.

72
00:07:34,994 --> 00:07:36,787
We had the best farm in the township.

73
00:07:36,954 --> 00:07:39,331
Yeah. Rockville Township it was.
Stone County.

74
00:07:39,499 --> 00:07:40,998
Oh, it was not.

75
00:07:41,166 --> 00:07:43,834
It was his itching foot
that brought us here.

76
00:07:44,002 --> 00:07:46,295
Heaven knows where we'll end up.

77
00:07:47,005 --> 00:07:50,841
Oh, these are my laddies.
Angus, Brutus and Colin.

78
00:07:51,009 --> 00:07:52,176
How do you do?
Hello.

79
00:07:52,344 --> 00:07:56,054
I think they're already acquainted
with your daughters.

80
00:07:56,305 --> 00:07:59,682
Be they single?
Aye, single so far.

81
00:07:59,850 --> 00:08:03,144
Well, this Illinois country's beginning
to sound better to me.

82
00:08:03,312 --> 00:08:04,354
Lilith?

83
00:08:04,522 --> 00:08:07,816
Lilith, here. Strike up a little tune
for these handsome lads.

84
00:08:07,983 --> 00:08:11,110
Oh, I ain't in no mood, Pa.
Lilith, there's a time for coaxing...

85
00:08:11,277 --> 00:08:12,986
...this ain't the time.

86
00:08:13,154 --> 00:08:18,867
All right.

87
00:08:20,703 --> 00:08:25,164
(SINGING) A captain bold in Halifax
Who lived in country quarters

88
00:08:25,332 --> 00:08:29,001
Betrayed a maid who hanged herself
One morning in her garters...

89
00:08:29,169 --> 00:08:30,461
ZEBULON:
Lilith.

90
00:08:30,629 --> 00:08:33,381
Now, you know better
than to sing a song like that.

91
00:08:33,549 --> 00:08:35,883
What ones do you know?
We know "Yankee Doodle."

92
00:08:36,051 --> 00:08:37,844
"Yankee Doodle"?
Their mother's dead.

93
00:08:38,011 --> 00:08:41,054
They haven't had much learning
in the social graces.

94
00:08:41,222 --> 00:08:43,682
All right. give then
"A Home in the Meadow."

95
00:08:43,850 --> 00:08:46,268
(SINGING "A HOME
IN THE MEADOW")

96
00:08:48,396 --> 00:08:50,897
Eve. come on, you too.

97
00:08:51,566 --> 00:08:53,108
That's it.

98
00:08:54,068 --> 00:08:55,734
Come on. join in.

99
00:08:55,902 --> 00:08:57,069
(ALL SINGING)

100
00:08:57,237 --> 00:08:59,029
That's it.

101
00:09:04,077 --> 00:09:05,828
Come on.

102
00:09:10,416 --> 00:09:12,750
Stop.

103
00:09:26,598 --> 00:09:29,474
Loading for the Flying Arrow!

104
00:09:29,642 --> 00:09:33,604
All aboard for the Flying Arrow!

105
00:09:34,105 --> 00:09:37,149
The Prescott family!
Here we be. Come on.

106
00:09:37,317 --> 00:09:41,277
Alec Harvey and three sons!

107
00:09:41,445 --> 00:09:44,906
Jeffrey Rose and family!

108
00:10:15,477 --> 00:10:19,772
But the canal was only the first step
toward the promised land.

109
00:10:19,940 --> 00:10:23,150
The next steps were longer and harder.

110
00:10:23,777 --> 00:10:28,154
Those who could raise the fare
went by steamboat to the end of the lime.

111
00:10:28,322 --> 00:10:31,783
Others found a cheaper way
to head for Ohio, Illinois...

112
00:10:31,951 --> 00:10:34,244
...and the open spaces beyond.

113
00:10:38,165 --> 00:10:41,041
(HUMMING)

114
00:10:50,260 --> 00:10:53,679
Lilith. Lilith. listen to this:

115
00:10:53,846 --> 00:10:57,306
"Theirs was a poignant parting
in the forest."

116
00:10:57,474 --> 00:11:01,852
The handsome young backwoodsman
carved two hearts on a tree trunk...

117
00:11:02,020 --> 00:11:06,399
"...then from ten paces, hurled a knife
at the junction of the two hearts."

118
00:11:06,566 --> 00:11:08,150
Junction. What's that?

119
00:11:09,361 --> 00:11:12,237
Well, that's where the two hearts meet.
Now, listen:

120
00:11:12,405 --> 00:11:14,823
"His marksmanship was uncanny."

121
00:11:14,991 --> 00:11:17,701
Three times he hurled
the knife on target.

122
00:11:18,009 --> 00:11:20,844
'That was for luck.' he
said the first time.

123
00:11:20,955 --> 00:11:24,582
'That was for love. Deep, divine love.'
he said the second.

124
00:11:24,750 --> 00:11:30,713
And the third time, 'That was a prayer,
a plea for love undying."'

125
00:11:30,880 --> 00:11:32,548
Isn't that beautiful?

126
00:11:33,675 --> 00:11:36,385
I reckon. If anybody ever talks like that.

127
00:11:37,262 --> 00:11:39,722
Well, it's the sentiments, not the talk.

128
00:11:40,389 --> 00:11:42,223
There ain't no sense to you. Eve.

129
00:11:42,391 --> 00:11:46,102
You wanna to be a farm wife,
but you don't wanna marry a farmer.

130
00:11:46,270 --> 00:11:48,313
Neither do you.

131
00:11:48,480 --> 00:11:49,522
Of course not.

132
00:11:49,690 --> 00:11:52,108
I don't wanna have
nothing to do with farms.

133
00:11:52,276 --> 00:11:57,279
I want silk dresses and fine carriages
and a man to smell good.

134
00:11:57,447 --> 00:12:00,282
What I want's back East, not West.

135
00:12:00,450 --> 00:12:02,743
But I'll get there yet. You watch.

136
00:12:03,411 --> 00:12:05,912
You don't know what you want yet.

137
00:12:06,122 --> 00:12:09,249
It's the nan that counts.
not where he lives.

138
00:12:16,673 --> 00:12:19,842
Ready, now?
MAN: Ready.

139
00:12:53,666 --> 00:12:59,504
Daddy, Daddy, something coming upriver.
Hostile Indians, I suspect.

140
00:13:20,149 --> 00:13:23,276
Could it be river pirates, Zebulon?
Don't know.

141
00:13:23,444 --> 00:13:25,820
They say no honest nan
travels this river at night.

142
00:13:25,987 --> 00:13:27,738
I can only see one man, Pa.

143
00:13:27,906 --> 00:13:31,117
I hear that's a favorite pirate trick.
They hide in the bottom of the boat...

144
00:13:31,284 --> 00:13:32,910
...till they're ready to jump you.

145
00:13:33,078 --> 00:13:36,080
Get my gun, Colin.
All right, Pa.

146
00:13:43,504 --> 00:13:45,338
Just come in slow and easy, stranger.

147
00:13:46,424 --> 00:13:49,342
And keep your hands
where we can see them.

148
00:14:06,776 --> 00:14:08,360
Name's Linus Rawlings.

149
00:14:08,528 --> 00:14:11,195
I'm hungrier than sin
and real peaceful like.

150
00:14:11,363 --> 00:14:13,531
What have you got in the craft?
Beaver pelts.

151
00:14:13,699 --> 00:14:16,200
I said beaver pelts.

152
00:14:16,368 --> 00:14:20,329
I never had a chance to see a beaver pelt,
Mr. Rawlings.

153
00:14:21,331 --> 00:14:24,417
Well, in that case, ma'am,
I'll show you one.

154
00:14:24,585 --> 00:14:26,418
There you are.

155
00:14:26,586 --> 00:14:28,670
That's real soft.

156
00:14:28,838 --> 00:14:30,088
It's a fine pelt, ma'am.

157
00:14:30,256 --> 00:14:31,631
ZEBULON:
Now, my apologies, sir.

158
00:14:33,134 --> 00:14:36,219
We was afeared you might be a pirate.
I ain't no pirate.

159
00:14:36,387 --> 00:14:39,431
Come on. let's have supper
and get acquainted.

160
00:14:39,931 --> 00:14:44,226
No, no, no. That's yours.
Keep that. ma'am.

161
00:14:58,407 --> 00:15:00,533
Well, you sure set your cap in a hurry.

162
00:15:00,701 --> 00:15:03,036
Is he the backwoodsman
you've been waiting for?

163
00:15:03,204 --> 00:15:07,081
More than likely he's got
a wife and six kids waiting for him.

164
00:15:11,711 --> 00:15:14,546
(LILITH SINGING)

165
00:15:32,439 --> 00:15:34,607
Thank you, ma'am, that was right tasty.

166
00:15:34,775 --> 00:15:38,152
You've only had four plates. I was
beginning to think you didn't like it.

167
00:15:38,320 --> 00:15:42,447
Well, it don't pay to eat too much
on an empty stomach. ma'am.

168
00:15:42,615 --> 00:15:44,991
How come you're to be traveling
so late at night?

169
00:15:45,159 --> 00:15:47,285
Well, I'm kind of anxious
to get to Pittsburgh.

170
00:15:47,453 --> 00:15:50,789
I ain't seen a city for a long time.
I aim to whoop it up a little.

171
00:15:51,082 --> 00:15:52,123
(CHUCKLES)

172
00:15:52,291 --> 00:15:54,543
Well, now. we've never seen
a mountain man before.

173
00:15:54,710 --> 00:15:58,254
Tell me, them Rocky Mountains
as high as they say?

174
00:15:58,421 --> 00:16:03,425
Well, now. I just don't rightly know.
I never climbed one. I've...

175
00:16:03,593 --> 00:16:05,094
Uh...

176
00:16:05,262 --> 00:16:09,640
Well, you know,
that just ain't exactly true.

177
00:16:09,807 --> 00:16:11,724
Jin Bridger and me...

178
00:16:11,892 --> 00:16:16,980
...we started up one of them little-bitty
Rocky Mountain foothills, you know.

179
00:16:17,481 --> 00:16:21,276
And then. one day. we see this fella...

180
00:16:21,443 --> 00:16:25,737
...and he has a great big pair
of white wings...

181
00:16:25,905 --> 00:16:27,573
...and a harp in his hand.

182
00:16:28,408 --> 00:16:30,284
And I said to Jim...

183
00:16:30,451 --> 00:16:34,246
...I said, "Jin, I don't like the way
that fella's looking at us."

184
00:16:34,414 --> 00:16:38,584
And Jim said he didn't care too much
for it neither...

185
00:16:38,751 --> 00:16:40,835
...so we both skedaddled down
out of there...

186
00:16:41,003 --> 00:16:45,006
...and to this day I ain't never had
a good look at the Rocky Mountains.

187
00:16:45,173 --> 00:16:47,341
(ACCORDION PLAYS)

188
00:16:50,804 --> 00:16:52,888
Well, I remember one time...
Zebulon.

189
00:16:53,056 --> 00:16:56,266
What?
One liar at a time is enough.

190
00:16:56,434 --> 00:16:57,892
(CHUCKLES)

191
00:16:58,060 --> 00:17:02,522
Well, then. I reckon it's about bedtime.
Gotta get an early start in the morning.

192
00:17:02,690 --> 00:17:04,524
We'll be expecting you for breakfast.

193
00:17:04,692 --> 00:17:07,027
Oh, well, that's mighty hospitable,
Mr. Prescott...

194
00:17:07,194 --> 00:17:09,571
...but sometimes I wake up
and get the urge to move.

195
00:17:09,739 --> 00:17:11,989
I night be long gone by sunup,
but thank you.

196
00:17:12,157 --> 00:17:15,701
I wanna thank all of you. Good night.
Good night.

197
00:17:16,911 --> 00:17:21,874
Strange fellas, these mountain men.
Yeah, kind of like a wisp of smoke.

198
00:17:41,392 --> 00:17:44,645
By golly. that looks like my blanket.
It is.

199
00:17:44,812 --> 00:17:48,273
Well, then. I'm a mite confused, ma'am.
Whose bed would it be?

200
00:17:48,441 --> 00:17:50,400
Yours.

201
00:17:51,027 --> 00:17:55,488
I ain't ever saw a bed like that
since last time I come east.

202
00:17:55,864 --> 00:17:57,698
Why'd you do it?

203
00:17:57,866 --> 00:18:01,118
Ain't polite to ask a girl
why she dome something for a nan.

204
00:18:01,703 --> 00:18:04,413
No. Well, I reckon my manners
ain't much at that.

205
00:18:04,581 --> 00:18:08,125
Anyway, I sure thank you.
Good night, ma'am.

206
00:18:12,755 --> 00:18:14,798
Are them Indian girls pretty?

207
00:18:14,965 --> 00:18:18,802
Well, now. I reckon that all depends
on just how long a nan has gone...

208
00:18:18,969 --> 00:18:21,054
...without seeing one.

209
00:18:21,931 --> 00:18:25,099
How long's it been
since you seen a white girl?

210
00:18:25,558 --> 00:18:28,060
I ain't quite sure why you asked that.

211
00:18:30,355 --> 00:18:32,356
How pretty do I look to you?

212
00:18:32,524 --> 00:18:34,233
But, ma'am...

213
00:18:34,567 --> 00:18:38,028
...ain't you just being
a little bit forward?

214
00:18:38,196 --> 00:18:43,282
Well, you're headed upriver
and I'm headed down.

215
00:18:43,450 --> 00:18:46,202
There's no time
to get these questions answered.

216
00:18:48,789 --> 00:18:51,374
You dead sure you want them answered?

217
00:18:53,335 --> 00:18:55,085
Yes.

218
00:19:08,307 --> 00:19:09,974
Glory be.

219
00:19:11,601 --> 00:19:13,936
Ma'am, it seems like
you've been kissed before.

220
00:19:16,440 --> 00:19:18,649
I've never been kissed permanent before.

221
00:19:20,152 --> 00:19:22,445
By golly, you sure use surprising words.

222
00:19:22,612 --> 00:19:26,781
I never heard "permanent" mixed up
with a thing like a kiss before.

223
00:19:28,534 --> 00:19:30,910
I can still feel that kiss.

224
00:19:31,078 --> 00:19:33,413
Can you?
Well, you said something before...

225
00:19:33,581 --> 00:19:35,331
...that we had not forget:

226
00:19:35,499 --> 00:19:39,335
I'm heading upstream
and you're headed downstream.

227
00:19:39,670 --> 00:19:42,004
Lovers have parted before
and come together again.

228
00:19:42,172 --> 00:19:43,589
Ma'am.
Eve.

229
00:19:45,508 --> 00:19:49,720
Eve. I'm a sinful man.

230
00:19:50,680 --> 00:19:52,514
Deep, dark, sinful.

231
00:19:52,682 --> 00:19:56,684
I'm on my way to Pittsburgh
to be sinful again.

232
00:19:56,852 --> 00:19:58,644
Likely I'll stay drunk for a month.

233
00:19:58,812 --> 00:20:01,522
I won't even remember
the fancy gals I dally with...

234
00:20:01,690 --> 00:20:04,567
...or the men I carve up
just out of pure cussedness...

235
00:20:04,735 --> 00:20:07,361
...any more than I'll remember you.

236
00:20:08,197 --> 00:20:12,824
Linus, I'm asking you.
Can you still feel that kiss?

237
00:20:12,992 --> 00:20:14,117
Eve...

238
00:20:16,162 --> 00:20:21,082
Eve. you make me feel like a man
standing on a narrow ledge...

239
00:20:21,250 --> 00:20:25,336
...coning face-to-face with a grizzly bear.

240
00:20:26,046 --> 00:20:30,674
There just ain't no ignoring the situation.

241
00:20:51,570 --> 00:20:58,826
Eve!

242
00:20:58,993 --> 00:21:01,245
Eve! Where is she?
Zeb, what's the matter?

243
00:21:01,412 --> 00:21:04,414
Anyways, you're here.
I thought you'd gone with him.

244
00:21:04,582 --> 00:21:07,584
Gone?
Yes, gone.

245
00:21:07,919 --> 00:21:09,919
I knowed you were setting with him...

246
00:21:10,087 --> 00:21:13,089
...but I kept telling myself,
"At least she's looking at a nan."

247
00:21:13,257 --> 00:21:17,009
Even a wisp of smoke like that
is better than...

248
00:21:19,096 --> 00:21:22,431
Are you crying? Crying for him?
Now, what does that mean?

249
00:21:23,559 --> 00:21:25,642
Now, tell me what that means.

250
00:21:26,769 --> 00:21:28,270
Nothing, Pa.

251
00:21:28,437 --> 00:21:30,605
What time did you come to bed?

252
00:21:30,940 --> 00:21:33,108
It was early. Pa.

253
00:21:33,442 --> 00:21:36,152
It wasn't. It was late.

254
00:21:36,320 --> 00:21:38,947
Daughter, I'm only gonna ask you once.

255
00:21:39,115 --> 00:21:42,533
Is there anything for your ma and pa
to worry about?

256
00:21:43,076 --> 00:21:45,202
No, Pa, there ain't.

257
00:22:01,886 --> 00:22:03,678
He'll be back.

258
00:22:04,179 --> 00:22:05,722
I'll see him again.

259
00:22:05,890 --> 00:22:09,642
But you expected to see him this morning.
You know you did.

260
00:22:09,810 --> 00:22:12,978
I don't care. I'll see him again.

261
00:22:13,396 --> 00:22:15,063
Look.

262
00:22:20,945 --> 00:22:26,616
You got a growed man to do that?
I did. Just like in the book.

263
00:22:26,783 --> 00:22:29,827
Did you get him to say then crazy words?

264
00:22:29,995 --> 00:22:33,122
I told you before, it ain't the words,
it's the sentiment.

265
00:22:34,207 --> 00:22:37,668
You mean, he didn't even giggle nor nothing
at such foolishness?

266
00:22:38,754 --> 00:22:41,963
He said it was a real solemn occasion.

267
00:22:42,131 --> 00:22:44,799
Like shooting the rapids without a paddle.

268
00:22:46,761 --> 00:22:50,639
No matter what he said, he did it just
to get rid of you so as he could clear out.

269
00:22:50,806 --> 00:22:52,933
You know that's so.

270
00:22:53,100 --> 00:22:56,936
And you're lucky he did. Do you wanna
live like a squaw all your life?

271
00:22:57,103 --> 00:22:59,563
Go on, say anything you like...

272
00:22:59,731 --> 00:23:02,650
...but I'll see him again. I know I will.

273
00:23:02,817 --> 00:23:05,110
And he ain't got a wife and six kids.

274
00:23:05,862 --> 00:23:08,489
He ain't got a wife at all yet.

275
00:23:21,585 --> 00:23:23,336
Hey, Pierre!

276
00:23:23,504 --> 00:23:24,836
Someone's coming upriver.

277
00:23:39,811 --> 00:23:40,935
Customer.

278
00:23:49,820 --> 00:23:51,404
Trapper, seems like.

279
00:23:51,571 --> 00:23:55,448
See how that cover bellies up?
Could be furs.

280
00:24:07,211 --> 00:24:08,837
Thirsty, mister?

281
00:24:09,005 --> 00:24:12,548
Drier than a grasshopper on a hot griddle.

282
00:24:15,760 --> 00:24:18,345
Well, welcome to our little inn, sir.

283
00:24:18,513 --> 00:24:21,515
My name is Jeb Hawkins,
late colonel of the Alabama militia.

284
00:24:21,683 --> 00:24:23,225
Where you bound for?
Pittsburgh.

285
00:24:23,393 --> 00:24:24,435
Pittsburgh? Well.

286
00:24:24,602 --> 00:24:27,145
Looks like he's got
a whole canoe of furs. Pop.

287
00:24:27,312 --> 00:24:29,522
Sure enough mountain nan.
Indeed.

288
00:24:29,690 --> 00:24:33,276
One of our explorers gonna extend our
domain to the far shores of the Pacific.

289
00:24:33,444 --> 00:24:35,778
Well, nothing but the finest for you, sir.
Whiskey?

290
00:24:35,946 --> 00:24:38,531
Right.
No pepper or rattlesnake heads in this.

291
00:24:38,699 --> 00:24:41,116
Nothing but the pure grain
and the sweet kiss of the malt.

292
00:24:41,284 --> 00:24:43,594
Never mind the cup,
I'll just take the jug.

293
00:24:43,625 --> 00:24:46,151
Oh, a real mountain man, huh?

294
00:24:46,289 --> 00:24:50,125
I trust you'll toast our noble banner, sir.
Sure will.

295
00:25:10,978 --> 00:25:13,146
Golly, you're right.
That's real sipping liquor.

296
00:25:13,314 --> 00:25:17,025
Pa, him being a trapper, you suppose he
might know what that varmint is we got?

297
00:25:17,193 --> 00:25:19,819
Well, say, now, he night.
Yes. sir, he just night.

298
00:25:20,154 --> 00:25:22,322
Sir. we caught us
a cave-dwelling critter...

299
00:25:22,490 --> 00:25:24,574
...that no nan in these parts
has seen before.

300
00:25:24,742 --> 00:25:27,993
You know, it'd be right satisfying
to having you tell us what it is.

301
00:25:28,328 --> 00:25:32,164
Well, I don't know too much
about cave-dwelling varmints.

302
00:25:32,332 --> 00:25:35,664
Just yonder. Take your jug.

303
00:25:36,166 --> 00:25:38,332
Well, I...

304
00:25:40,334 --> 00:25:42,333
I don't know.

305
00:25:59,088 --> 00:26:01,213
WOMAN:
It's right over here.

306
00:26:11,508 --> 00:26:13,673
You know any sweet-talking gals
in Pittsburgh?

307
00:26:13,841 --> 00:26:16,508
No, no. Nary a one, yet.

308
00:26:16,675 --> 00:26:19,008
Well, Pop and I are hoping
we'll vacation there.

309
00:26:19,176 --> 00:26:23,134
I'll be at the Duquesne House
if it ain't burned down.

310
00:26:23,302 --> 00:26:29,803
Hey, there. now, you pretty girl,
you sure you got a varmint in here?

311
00:26:30,011 --> 00:26:31,469
Now, you...

312
00:26:31,637 --> 00:26:33,261
WOMAN: Do you hear him?
RAWLINGS: Huh?

313
00:26:33,429 --> 00:26:35,887
WOMAN:
He breathes loud and fierce.

314
00:26:36,055 --> 00:26:40,262
We keep him in this hole just yonder.
RAWLINGS: You keep him in there?

315
00:26:42,348 --> 00:26:44,847
You gotta look a little closer.

316
00:26:52,517 --> 00:26:54,516
(GRUNTS)

317
00:26:56,184 --> 00:26:57,600
(SPLASHES)

318
00:27:04,520 --> 00:27:06,352
Well, he seen the varmint, Pa.

319
00:27:06,520 --> 00:27:09,478
Well dome. daughter.
I ain't so sure.

320
00:27:09,646 --> 00:27:13,020
He was hard muscled. I could feel
the blade just skitter along his ribs.

321
00:27:13,188 --> 00:27:15,312
Oh, you just meed more practice,
that's all.

322
00:27:15,480 --> 00:27:17,854
It's a pity you ain't got the knack
your ma had.

323
00:27:18,022 --> 00:27:20,022
Lord rest her soul.

324
00:27:20,190 --> 00:27:22,356
All right. men, lay it on, men.

325
00:27:22,524 --> 00:27:25,482
Come on. come on.
We got more fish to fry.

326
00:27:25,649 --> 00:27:27,774
Down to the island.

327
00:28:24,496 --> 00:28:27,371
Tell Pa them settlers' rafts are coning.

328
00:28:51,794 --> 00:28:53,543
Can't I have this toilet water, Pa?

329
00:28:53,710 --> 00:28:56,669
Genuine Parisian accent. it says.
How much is it?

330
00:28:56,837 --> 00:28:58,419
It's only 15 cents.

331
00:28:58,587 --> 00:29:00,503
Fifteen cents? Put it back.

332
00:29:00,671 --> 00:29:04,879
You're right, sir. Absolutely right.
You save the pennies and dollars will grow.

333
00:29:05,047 --> 00:29:06,671
Likely you've growed many a dollar.

334
00:29:06,839 --> 00:29:10,380
Mr. Bedloe, all my life I've been striving
to avoid becoming a millionaire.

335
00:29:10,548 --> 00:29:12,339
I think I've succeeded right well.

336
00:29:12,507 --> 00:29:15,132
I've got a little put away in the sock.
It'll stay there.

337
00:29:15,299 --> 00:29:17,674
Well, now. then's my sentiments exactly.

338
00:29:17,842 --> 00:29:20,383
Now, you, sir.
You look like a man of property.

339
00:29:20,551 --> 00:29:24,716
Now, if I was to bet, I'd say
you was worth, say, a thousand dollars.

340
00:29:24,884 --> 00:29:27,884
Pretty close to the nark?
Well, close, maybe.

341
00:30:23,481 --> 00:30:27,565
ALEC: Colin. how much powder we got left?
Don't be afraid. now, don't be afraid.

342
00:30:27,732 --> 00:30:29,481
Now, there's women and children here.

343
00:30:29,649 --> 00:30:32,899
You gents wouldn't want us to have
to start shooting, now, would you?

344
00:30:33,650 --> 00:30:35,150
Be of good cheer, folks.

345
00:30:35,317 --> 00:30:38,109
It's in our noble tradition
that we conquer the wilderness...

346
00:30:38,276 --> 00:30:40,693
...with nothing but our bare hands
and stout hearts.

347
00:30:40,860 --> 00:30:44,776
You can build mew rafts and sally forth
in the spirit of your forefathers.

348
00:30:44,944 --> 00:30:47,153
Why, you pious old scoundrel.

349
00:30:48,028 --> 00:30:49,570
I'll see you burn.

350
00:30:49,821 --> 00:30:51,778
(BEDLOE LAUGHING)

351
00:30:57,406 --> 00:30:58,822
BEDLOE:
Americans can't be whipped.

352
00:30:59,364 --> 00:31:00,905
(SCREAMS)

353
00:31:01,073 --> 00:31:04,322
It's him.
I knew he'd come back. It's him.

354
00:31:06,283 --> 00:31:47,583
(SCREAMS)

355
00:32:00,753 --> 00:32:04,378
Now let us pray.

356
00:32:05,588 --> 00:32:07,670
O Lord...

357
00:32:08,714 --> 00:32:11,504
...we thank thee for our salvation.

358
00:32:11,672 --> 00:32:15,338
We commit the souls of our dead
to thy gentle keeping.

359
00:32:15,965 --> 00:32:18,715
We pray for a speedy recovery
of our wounded.

360
00:32:21,883 --> 00:32:24,465
And now another matter.

361
00:32:24,967 --> 00:32:27,049
O Lord...

362
00:32:27,426 --> 00:32:29,884
...without consulting with thee...

363
00:32:30,051 --> 00:32:35,427
...we have sent thy way some souls
whose evil ways passeth all understanding.

364
00:32:36,094 --> 00:32:39,011
We ask thee humbly to receive then.

365
00:32:39,804 --> 00:32:41,761
Whether you want them or not.

366
00:32:41,929 --> 00:32:43,429
Amen.

367
00:33:05,059 --> 00:33:06,267
Now, it'll be a job...

368
00:33:06,435 --> 00:33:09,767
...but I guess I can patch her up
good enough to get to Pittsburgh.

369
00:33:10,311 --> 00:33:12,102
Linus.
Now, Eve...

370
00:33:12,269 --> 00:33:15,352
...let's just not talk any more about it.

371
00:33:15,520 --> 00:33:18,936
Linus, I'm telling you,
you don't know your own mind.

372
00:33:19,104 --> 00:33:21,146
Well, maybe so, maybe not.

373
00:33:21,313 --> 00:33:24,730
You know, I ain't saying
that you haven't been on my mind some.

374
00:33:24,898 --> 00:33:26,396
I ain't saying that.

375
00:33:26,564 --> 00:33:29,898
But I still went to see the varmint
with that pirate girl.

376
00:33:30,065 --> 00:33:33,106
I'll always be
going to see the varmint, Eve.

377
00:33:33,274 --> 00:33:37,274
I just ain't cut out
to be a farmer or a husband.

378
00:33:38,442 --> 00:33:41,483
Linus, I ain't never bringing up
the subject again...

379
00:33:41,651 --> 00:33:43,442
...whether ever I see you or not.

380
00:33:43,610 --> 00:33:46,109
No, it's for the best.

381
00:33:46,527 --> 00:33:49,319
I wish you Godspeed, Eve.

382
00:33:49,486 --> 00:33:54,195
And I ain't said that to anybody
for a long time.

383
00:34:27,828 --> 00:34:30,953
I can see rapids ahead. Pa. White water.

384
00:34:31,120 --> 00:34:32,453
Look. Look.

385
00:34:32,621 --> 00:34:34,537
Oh, we must've taken the wrong fork.

386
00:34:34,705 --> 00:34:37,079
Let's beach her on this side.

387
00:34:37,247 --> 00:34:39,580
Harvey!

388
00:34:40,164 --> 00:34:41,663
Rapids!

389
00:34:41,831 --> 00:34:44,289
Rapids ahead! Beach her!

390
00:34:44,457 --> 00:34:45,789
Beach her!

391
00:34:49,249 --> 00:34:51,291
REBECCA:
Hold her steady.

392
00:34:56,543 --> 00:34:58,792
Rein!

393
00:34:59,127 --> 00:35:01,418
Pa, we're in the current!

394
00:35:05,045 --> 00:35:07,253
Get inside, Zeke.

395
00:35:07,420 --> 00:35:10,253
ZEKE:
No, I don't wanna.

396
00:35:15,631 --> 00:35:18,172
Straighten her. Pa.

397
00:35:19,256 --> 00:35:21,131
Lilith!

398
00:35:40,595 --> 00:35:43,053
Hold it steady!

399
00:35:44,887 --> 00:35:47,179
EVE:
I can't!

400
00:37:02,571 --> 00:37:05,488
Go on. Go on to help Pa.

401
00:37:05,656 --> 00:37:07,489
I'll get it.

402
00:37:11,823 --> 00:37:14,240
(LILITH SCREAMS)

403
00:37:22,952 --> 00:37:25,992
REBECCA:
Lilith! Lilith!

404
00:38:00,668 --> 00:38:05,252
Lie down!

405
00:38:41,219 --> 00:38:42,510
RAWLINGS:
What happened?

406
00:38:42,678 --> 00:38:46,511
They took the wrong fork of the river
and they went over the falls.

407
00:38:46,679 --> 00:38:48,761
RAWLINGS: Did you happen to hear
the name of the family?

408
00:38:48,929 --> 00:38:52,553
Uh... Prescott, I think.
Something like that.

409
00:39:06,641 --> 00:39:08,724
As soon as they're buried decent...

410
00:39:08,892 --> 00:39:11,849
...I'm heading back East
on the first boat that comes along.

411
00:39:12,017 --> 00:39:16,059
And if you were in your right mind,
you would too.

412
00:39:45,192 --> 00:39:47,483
Oh, Linus.

413
00:40:15,532 --> 00:40:19,782
(SINGING "ROCK OF AGES")

414
00:41:11,545 --> 00:41:14,378
Would you walk with me a piece, Eve?

415
00:41:34,133 --> 00:41:35,300
Eve. I...

416
00:41:37,217 --> 00:41:42,509
Eve. all the time I was paddling down here
I was thinking...

417
00:41:42,677 --> 00:41:46,552
...if I found you alive, I'd...

418
00:41:47,136 --> 00:41:50,469
Would you come
to Pittsburgh with me, Eve?

419
00:41:51,012 --> 00:41:53,220
Oh, Linus.

420
00:41:54,846 --> 00:41:57,054
I'm staying right here.

421
00:41:57,222 --> 00:42:00,221
I ain't moving a foot
one way or the other.

422
00:42:01,806 --> 00:42:04,180
Now, would you explain that a little?

423
00:42:06,182 --> 00:42:09,348
Ma and Pa,
they wanted a farm in the West...

424
00:42:09,516 --> 00:42:12,141
...and this is as far as they got.

425
00:42:13,058 --> 00:42:16,392
Seems to me this is where the Lord
wanted the farm to be.

426
00:42:16,560 --> 00:42:19,268
But your brother, San, he's bad hurt,
and winter's coning...

427
00:42:19,435 --> 00:42:21,852
There's no sense talking about it.
I'm gonna do it.

428
00:42:22,185 --> 00:42:24,560
Eve. you just ain't making much sense.

429
00:42:26,228 --> 00:42:30,228
Well, half the people that come West
don't make much sense, I reckon.

430
00:42:35,188 --> 00:42:39,063
All right.

431
00:42:40,356 --> 00:42:43,981
By golly, you're a strong-minded woman.

432
00:42:45,816 --> 00:42:50,233
I reckon I seen that varmint
for the last time.

433
00:43:13,114 --> 00:43:16,989
(HORN BLOWS)

434
00:43:36,077 --> 00:43:40,827
The westward course was no smoother
than that of true love.

435
00:43:40,995 --> 00:43:45,412
Not only the hard hand of nature
was against it, but the impediment of war.

436
00:43:45,580 --> 00:43:49,121
Trouble over land
smoldered along the Mexican border.

437
00:43:49,289 --> 00:43:53,913
Not all Americans were for war, including
Congressman Abe Lincoln of Illinois.

438
00:43:54,081 --> 00:43:57,081
But a war did break out,
and in the end...

439
00:43:57,249 --> 00:44:01,082
...vast mew territories came into the Union
along with their rich Spanish names:

440
00:44:01,250 --> 00:44:05,167
Rio Grande, Santa Fe,
Albuquerque, El Paso.

441
00:44:05,335 --> 00:44:08,292
And most glittering of all, California...

442
00:44:08,460 --> 00:44:13,168
...named after a mythical island of
pearls and gold in a 15th-century novel.

443
00:44:13,336 --> 00:44:16,169
Here, in 1848...

444
00:44:16,337 --> 00:44:19,878
...at Sutter's Mill, a man found something
he wasn't even looking for...

445
00:44:20,046 --> 00:44:21,503
...at the bottom of a ditch.

446
00:44:21,671 --> 00:44:24,795
And the cry of his discovery was heard
clear across the continent...

447
00:44:24,963 --> 00:44:26,713
...in Boston, New York, Savannah...

448
00:44:26,881 --> 00:44:30,380
...and across the oceans
in London, Paris, Berlin.

449
00:44:30,548 --> 00:44:36,757
But nowhere was the clamor of gold
heard more eagerly than in St. Louis...

450
00:44:36,924 --> 00:44:39,424
...the busiest fur-trading center
in the world...

451
00:44:39,592 --> 00:44:43,842
...and the noisiest, bawdiest,
most uppity town west of New York.

452
00:44:48,344 --> 00:44:50,594
(MUSIC PLAYING)

453
00:45:11,349 --> 00:45:14,140
(SINGING)

454
00:45:33,395 --> 00:45:35,020
