to California to claim the bequest.

476
00:46:38,077 --> 00:46:40,452
Well, now. I wouldn't go to California...

477
00:46:40,619 --> 00:46:43,535
...if John Jacob Astor left me
San Francisco.

478
00:46:43,703 --> 00:46:46,286
I don't think Mr. Astor
had holdings there, no.

479
00:46:46,454 --> 00:46:49,620
However, the yield from
Mr. Brooks' property is not to be scorned.

480
00:46:49,788 --> 00:46:54,080
Yield of what?
Gold, Miss Prescott. Gold.

481
00:46:54,247 --> 00:46:56,163
Gold?
Precisely.

482
00:46:56,331 --> 00:47:01,998
You own a gold mine, Miss Prescott.
It yielded $3500 the very first week.

483
00:47:02,166 --> 00:47:04,290
LILITH:
Gold mine?

484
00:47:06,625 --> 00:47:09,208
Well. Well, I...

485
00:47:09,376 --> 00:47:12,125
That sweet old goat.

486
00:47:15,419 --> 00:47:17,418
For heavens...

487
00:47:28,880 --> 00:47:30,630
Well.

488
00:47:30,798 --> 00:47:32,463
This is an unexpected pleasure.

489
00:47:32,631 --> 00:47:34,880
Where's the money?
Money?

490
00:47:35,048 --> 00:47:36,131
Money?

491
00:47:36,298 --> 00:47:40,215
Oh, yes. You're referring, of course.
to our little agreement.

492
00:47:40,966 --> 00:47:43,216
One hundred to start you off...

493
00:47:43,384 --> 00:47:45,175
...and my share of the winnings.

494
00:47:46,634 --> 00:47:51,259
Well, I'm somewhat embarrassed to report
that the hundred no longer exists.

495
00:47:53,302 --> 00:47:55,177
That $100, I assure you...

496
00:47:55,345 --> 00:47:59,928
...will turn out to be the best investment
you have ever made.

497
00:48:00,096 --> 00:48:02,012
I have plans, gentlemen...

498
00:48:02,179 --> 00:48:04,970
...beyond your wildest dreams.

499
00:48:05,138 --> 00:48:08,971
I'm gonna earn you
a piece of a gold mime.

500
00:48:09,306 --> 00:48:11,430
Gold mine.

501
00:48:11,807 --> 00:48:13,640
You ain't gonna earn nothing.

502
00:48:13,807 --> 00:48:16,598
You ain't gonna be nothing.
you ain't gonna do nothing...

503
00:48:16,766 --> 00:48:19,015
...unless we get that 100 back
by the morning.

504
00:48:19,183 --> 00:48:21,474
Grimes, you don't mean that.

505
00:48:21,642 --> 00:48:25,475
You're gonna kill off the golden goose.
Call it what you want. mister.

506
00:48:25,643 --> 00:48:27,559
We'll be waiting.

507
00:48:49,981 --> 00:48:55,232
Independence, Missouri, was the jump-off
point for emigrants from everywhere.

508
00:48:55,400 --> 00:48:59,817
Solid, God-fearing families
bound for the farmlands of Oregon...

509
00:48:59,984 --> 00:49:05,151
...and get-rich-quick adventurers
racing for the gold of California.

510
00:49:07,736 --> 00:49:09,485
Try it.

511
00:49:14,654 --> 00:49:17,487
You got a wagon. I suppose?
I can get one.

512
00:49:17,655 --> 00:49:18,904
And a team to pull it?

513
00:49:19,072 --> 00:49:20,446
I can get everything I meed.

514
00:49:21,280 --> 00:49:24,656
You got a husband?
I'm single. Mr. Morgan.

515
00:49:24,823 --> 00:49:27,115
No traveling companion?

516
00:49:27,282 --> 00:49:30,448
No, I'm traveling alone.
Not on my wagon train.

517
00:49:31,449 --> 00:49:34,116
Alone and single brings out
the deviltry in a man.

518
00:49:34,283 --> 00:49:37,617
Gets then all worked up
and they're wild enough already.

519
00:49:37,784 --> 00:49:40,159
I intend to keep to myself, Mr. Morgan.

520
00:49:41,327 --> 00:49:43,576
Oh, woman of your sort?

521
00:49:43,786 --> 00:49:45,883
One day you'd find
yourself in trouble, and

522
00:49:45,914 --> 00:49:48,566
there'd be hell to pay
just figuring out who.

523
00:49:48,703 --> 00:49:52,120
What did you say, Mr. Morgan?

524
00:49:52,413 --> 00:49:57,162
Well, now. ain't you the feisty one.
I like spirit in a woman.

525
00:49:57,330 --> 00:50:01,622
Hey, you got a pretty face
under that powder too.

526
00:50:01,790 --> 00:50:05,581
And a fine, sturdy body
under then clothes, I wager.

527
00:50:07,666 --> 00:50:10,666
There's a woman named Clegg.
Aggie Clegg.

528
00:50:10,834 --> 00:50:12,874
Why don't you go see her?

529
00:50:20,794 --> 00:50:22,585
Thanks.

530
00:50:31,547 --> 00:50:33,629
I told you, no.

531
00:50:33,797 --> 00:50:36,672
I was hoping to make this trip
with a husband.

532
00:50:36,840 --> 00:50:38,256
Nearly got one last week.

533
00:50:38,673 --> 00:50:42,424
Look. I hear there's 40 men
to every woman in California.

534
00:50:42,590 --> 00:50:46,174
Miss Clegg. I'd be willing to pay you.
I don't meed money.

535
00:50:46,341 --> 00:50:48,675
I meed a nan.

536
00:50:49,676 --> 00:50:51,800
Any man.

537
00:50:58,511 --> 00:51:00,593
Morning, ladies.

538
00:51:01,178 --> 00:51:03,261
Beautiful morning.

539
00:51:03,846 --> 00:51:07,720
Would you, by any chance.
happen to be Miss Lily Prescott?

540
00:51:08,055 --> 00:51:10,471
Not unless you got a big imagination.

541
00:51:10,639 --> 00:51:13,180
Then you must be the lady in question.

542
00:51:13,348 --> 00:51:15,764
Cleve Van Valen, Miss Prescott,
at your service.

543
00:51:15,932 --> 00:51:18,681
At your every command
from here to California.

544
00:51:18,849 --> 00:51:20,056
Well, thank you.

545
00:51:20,224 --> 00:51:22,433
But whatever you're offering,
I don't meed.

546
00:51:22,599 --> 00:51:23,599
(CHUCKLES)

547
00:51:23,767 --> 00:51:25,016
Perhaps you don't understand.

548
00:51:25,183 --> 00:51:26,183
(LAUGHS)

549
00:51:26,351 --> 00:51:29,434
Yes. I do.
I know a tin-horn when I see one.

550
00:51:29,601 --> 00:51:31,017
Miss Prescott.

551
00:51:31,185 --> 00:51:34,226
I'm offering you an honest day's work
for an honest day's pay.

552
00:51:34,394 --> 00:51:38,019
Goodbye, Mr. Van Valen. Goodbye.

553
00:51:39,062 --> 00:51:41,728
Well, it's been a pleasure to meet you.
Miss Clegg.

554
00:51:41,896 --> 00:51:47,396
May I say I have never seen a woman
with more beautiful hair.

555
00:51:47,564 --> 00:51:49,688
What a prize catch it'll make...

556
00:51:49,856 --> 00:51:52,647
...hanging from the waist of an Indian.

557
00:51:53,023 --> 00:51:57,690
Beauty alone in the wilderness,
and who's to protect you?

558
00:51:57,858 --> 00:51:58,940
No one.

559
00:51:59,108 --> 00:52:04,233
Not one person
won't be looking after himself.

560
00:52:06,026 --> 00:52:07,609
Well...

561
00:52:09,569 --> 00:52:13,277
Good day. ladies. Good day.

562
00:52:17,112 --> 00:52:20,362
Nobody ever said that to me before.

563
00:52:20,530 --> 00:52:22,320
What?

564
00:52:22,655 --> 00:52:26,530
That I had such... Such beautiful hair.

565
00:52:29,365 --> 00:52:31,531
You know something?

566
00:52:31,699 --> 00:52:36,199
I got a hunch you're gonna draw men
like fish to the bait.

567
00:52:36,366 --> 00:52:40,283
Maybe I can catch one of then
while they swim by.

568
00:52:41,034 --> 00:52:43,492
You got yourself a partner.

569
00:52:43,660 --> 00:52:45,076
Thank you.

570
00:52:46,702 --> 00:52:48,618
MAN 1:
How's it, men?

571
00:52:49,078 --> 00:52:50,974
MAN 2: It's all clear through here.
Look for

572
00:52:51,005 --> 00:52:52,900
a little mud-hole up
through the next pocket.

573
00:52:53,037 --> 00:52:55,036
MAN 1: How far?
MAN 2: Oh, maybe half a quarter.

574
00:52:55,067 --> 00:52:56,117
MAN 1: Well, thanks.

575
00:52:56,148 --> 00:52:58,234
MAN 2: Looks a little
higher up on that ridge.

576
00:52:58,371 --> 00:53:02,246
MAN 1: There's a water hole up there
about half a mile. Let's head for it.

577
00:53:09,583 --> 00:53:12,291
MAN 3:
Water hole about a half a mile ahead.

578
00:53:16,375 --> 00:53:18,709
Hey, you're driving.

579
00:53:19,126 --> 00:53:21,959
I was raised on a farm.

580
00:53:25,170 --> 00:53:26,835
MAN 3:
Water hole about a half a mile ahead.

581
00:54:05,304 --> 00:54:06,470
Hey, Aggie?

582
00:54:08,054 --> 00:54:10,970
Can you use these?
AGGIE: Yeah. sure.

583
00:54:11,138 --> 00:54:12,971
Thanks.

584
00:54:25,725 --> 00:54:27,224
Ladies.

585
00:54:36,602 --> 00:54:38,477
At your service.

586
00:54:38,644 --> 00:54:40,227
LILITH:
I thought we'd gotten rid of you.

587
00:54:40,395 --> 00:54:44,145
Well, I just couldn't bear to think of
you two making this trip without my help.

588
00:54:44,312 --> 00:54:48,187
If I was to hear later on that something
happened to you, I'd never forgive myself.

589
00:54:48,354 --> 00:54:49,812
You came 100 miles alone?

590
00:54:49,980 --> 00:54:54,481
Well, I had no way of counting the miles.
Mr. Morgan. but I'll take your word for it.

591
00:54:54,648 --> 00:54:56,898
Well, you've got another 100, mister.
Going back.

592
00:54:57,065 --> 00:55:00,231
I told you, when a wagon breaks down,
I want men who can fix it...

593
00:55:00,399 --> 00:55:02,149
...not bet how long it'll take.

594
00:55:02,317 --> 00:55:03,982
You don't mean you'll turn me out?

595
00:55:04,150 --> 00:55:06,733
Pass me adrift at the mercy
of savage Indians?

596
00:55:06,901 --> 00:55:09,066
If you don't get moving.
I'll cast you adrift...

597
00:55:09,234 --> 00:55:12,026
Uh-uh-uh.
I appeal to your sporting instinct, sir.

598
00:55:12,194 --> 00:55:15,485
I'm prepared to wager you
that I stay with this train.

599
00:55:15,652 --> 00:55:18,569
Well, you got a wager.
Wait a minute, wait a minute.

600
00:55:18,737 --> 00:55:20,569
The fact is, I hired this man.

601
00:55:20,737 --> 00:55:23,195
We'll put up his stake.

602
00:55:25,405 --> 00:55:27,237
Is that right, Miss Prescott?

603
00:55:27,405 --> 00:55:29,946
If Miss Clegg says so.

604
00:55:40,617 --> 00:55:42,325
Ma'am...

605
00:55:42,825 --> 00:55:44,575
...l'll be forever grateful.

606
00:55:48,327 --> 00:55:51,155
Now, I'll unpack my gear.

607
00:55:54,775 --> 00:55:57,440
Agatha, have you gone crazy?

608
00:55:57,608 --> 00:56:00,607
He says he's a nan
wanting to do an honest day's work.

609
00:56:01,775 --> 00:56:04,941
And he'll do it. I can promise you that.

610
00:56:05,817 --> 00:56:08,899
Hey, you men on that last wagon,
keep up that slack.

611
00:56:09,067 --> 00:56:10,856
Keep it up.

612
00:56:11,274 --> 00:56:14,691
Get that team moving.
Keep them moving there.

613
00:56:17,275 --> 00:56:20,024
Don't let those limes sag.

614
00:56:21,233 --> 00:56:23,649
Keep them up. Keep them up.

615
00:56:27,316 --> 00:56:29,816
Keep those teams moving.

616
00:56:31,650 --> 00:56:33,691
Keep them moving.

617
00:56:34,400 --> 00:56:37,191
Don't let those limes sag.

618
00:56:37,608 --> 00:56:40,816
You, on that middle team,
keep them moving.

619
00:56:50,775 --> 00:56:52,400
AGGIE: Get in there.
MAN: Over here, Pa.

620
00:56:52,566 --> 00:56:54,315
AGGIE:
Get in there.

621
00:56:55,234 --> 00:56:58,940
Get in there. Get in there, mule.

622
00:57:16,191 --> 00:57:17,981
(CHUCKLING)

623
00:57:32,274 --> 00:57:36,691
I'm just overwhelmed by all this attention,
Miss Prescott.

624
00:57:44,109 --> 00:57:46,191
I want to confess...

625
00:57:46,358 --> 00:57:51,273
...I have lied about
why I wanted to work for you.

626
00:57:51,441 --> 00:57:53,148
I know.

627
00:57:54,108 --> 00:57:57,690
The real reason is, of course,
that I'm in love with you.

628
00:57:57,858 --> 00:57:59,190
No.

629
00:57:59,358 --> 00:58:00,648
It's the truth.

630
00:58:00,815 --> 00:58:06,643
From the first moment I saw you, I've
known that I couldn't live without you.

631
00:58:07,394 --> 00:58:12,431
Well, I'd hate to be the cause
of your death, Mr. Van Valen.

632
00:58:12,599 --> 00:58:14,721
I don't speak lightly. Miss Prescott.

633
00:58:14,889 --> 00:58:19,176
I'm prepared to assume
the responsibilities of a faithful husband.

634
00:58:19,344 --> 00:58:22,632
Oh, and are you ready to assume
the responsibilities...

635
00:58:22,800 --> 00:58:25,213
...of my property too, Mr. Van Valen?

636
00:58:26,254 --> 00:58:28,128
Really?

637
00:58:28,295 --> 00:58:29,919
What kind of property?

638
00:58:31,044 --> 00:58:33,083
Gold, Mr. Van Valen.

639
00:58:33,250 --> 00:58:36,330
Gold by the ton, from what I understand.

640
00:58:36,498 --> 00:58:40,495
Bright. yellow, shiny gold.

641
00:58:41,912 --> 00:58:45,240
Why, I had no idea.

642
00:58:46,574 --> 00:58:49,779
I'm sure you hadn't.
Miss Prescott. I really mean...

643
00:58:49,947 --> 00:58:54,817
Here comes Agatha.
If you must propose to somebody...

644
00:58:54,985 --> 00:58:57,607
...I suggest you get on your knees to her.

645
00:58:57,775 --> 00:59:01,313
Besides. she has beautiful hair.

646
00:59:02,729 --> 00:59:04,603
Look at then.

647
00:59:04,770 --> 00:59:07,600
Think they was getting ready
to bury somebody.

648
00:59:07,768 --> 00:59:10,598
Ain't we worn down enough as it is?

649
00:59:10,765 --> 00:59:14,346
Well, let's wake them up.

650
00:59:17,385 --> 00:59:18,892
Listen, everybody.

651
00:59:20,106 --> 00:59:22,786
(SINGING)

652
01:00:38,560 --> 01:00:41,866
That's the spirit! That's the way to feel!

653
01:00:42,035 --> 01:00:44,503
(YELLS)

654
01:00:50,658 --> 01:00:53,378
Oh, hiya, Mr. Morgan!

655
01:01:06,274 --> 01:01:08,870
Aggie. For lunch.

656
01:01:09,035 --> 01:01:12,415
Thanks. Nice nest of fish.

657
01:01:19,630 --> 01:01:21,938
LILITH:
What is it, Mr. Morgan?

658
01:01:22,187 --> 01:01:25,031
Miss Prescott, I've been thinking.

659
01:01:26,021 --> 01:01:27,669
Oh?

660
01:01:29,690 --> 01:01:33,111
Wet or dry. you're the handsomest woman
I ever did see.

661
01:01:33,277 --> 01:01:35,914
Spirit and a fine, sturdy body.

662
01:01:36,246 --> 01:01:38,718
It's a noble combination, Miss Prescott.

663
01:01:38,884 --> 01:01:43,005
Why, for you, childbearing would
come as easy as rolling off a log.

664
01:01:44,944 --> 01:01:48,694
Well, I think I'd rather roll off a log.
Mr. Morgan.

665
01:01:49,437 --> 01:01:51,911
Ma'am, I'm telling you,
you got the build for it.

666
01:01:52,694 --> 01:01:55,084
I want you for my wife.

667
01:01:55,373 --> 01:01:57,970
I've got a cattle ranch
just below the Merced.

668
01:01:58,796 --> 01:02:01,228
I'll be settling down
there, fit and proper.

669
01:02:02,753 --> 01:02:05,721
I'm sure you're very fit and proper,
Mr. Morgan.

670
01:02:06,422 --> 01:02:07,970
Well, then...

671
01:02:08,138 --> 01:02:11,026
...you just couldn't do no better
than marrying me.

672
01:02:11,404 --> 01:02:14,962
Why, we'd have ourselves a fine family
in no time at all.

673
01:02:16,344 --> 01:02:18,603
I believe that.

674
01:02:19,525 --> 01:02:21,408
I'm sorry, Mr. Morgan...

675
01:02:22,581 --> 01:02:24,296
...but I can't accept your proposal.

676
01:02:24,464 --> 01:02:26,012
Why not?

677
01:02:26,766 --> 01:02:31,119
Well, a woman likes to hear something
a little more inviting.

678
01:02:32,375 --> 01:02:35,388
Well, ain't that what I've been doing?
Inviting you?

679
01:02:36,018 --> 01:02:38,194
Inviting you to share my life,
Miss Prescott.

680
01:02:41,627 --> 01:02:44,222
I'm sorry, Mr. Morgan.

681
01:02:45,771 --> 01:02:47,863
It's something else, ain't it?

682
01:02:48,827 --> 01:02:51,128
Must be something else nagging at you.

683
01:02:52,218 --> 01:02:54,058
Well...

684
01:02:54,687 --> 01:02:57,533
...I don't aim to let it stop me,
Miss Prescott.

685
01:02:58,832 --> 01:03:00,630
You can count on that.

686
01:03:00,799 --> 01:03:02,892
AGGIE:
What did he want?

687
01:03:04,022 --> 01:03:05,905
Children.

688
01:03:06,325 --> 01:03:07,873
Children?

689
01:03:08,041 --> 01:03:10,426
Well, I'll be...

690
01:03:10,595 --> 01:03:13,900
Why didn't he come shopping
at the right store?

691
01:03:33,157 --> 01:03:35,920
(MAN SPEAKING IN NATIVE LANGUAGE)

692
01:03:57,143 --> 01:03:59,654
I'll take a look.
Well.

693
01:03:59,822 --> 01:04:01,998
Now, gentlemen, are we pikers?

694
01:04:02,166 --> 01:04:05,220
I'm gonna see
and I'm gonna raise this fine pistol...

695
01:04:05,389 --> 01:04:08,277
...London-made and loaded for bear.

696
01:04:08,571 --> 01:04:11,165
MAN:
I'll take part of that bet.

697
01:04:17,780 --> 01:04:20,835
I told you I wouldn't stand
for you fleecing any...

698
01:04:23,892 --> 01:04:24,979
Cheyennes.

699
01:04:26,236 --> 01:04:28,663
There's too many to fight.
We'll have to run for it.

700
01:04:28,832 --> 01:04:30,421
You can't outrun then with wagons.

701
01:04:30,590 --> 01:04:32,807
The minute you get moving,
cut your teams loose.

702
01:04:32,975 --> 01:04:34,900
Have you gone crazy?
Go on, get moving.

703
01:04:35,068 --> 01:04:37,118
Chances are they want our stock
more than us.

704
01:04:37,287 --> 01:04:40,216
Now, you're a gambler. ain't you?
All right. let's get moving.

705
01:04:40,385 --> 01:04:42,645
(YELLING)

706
01:04:57,212 --> 01:04:59,416
Keep them closed up there.

707
01:05:10,775 --> 01:05:13,103
I don't know how to unhook them.

708
01:05:50,296 --> 01:05:51,959
(YELLS)

709
01:06:17,252 --> 01:06:18,915
Cleve, watch out!

710
01:06:53,694 --> 01:06:54,776
Cleve!

711
01:07:11,626 --> 01:07:13,163
(SCREAMS)

712
01:07:20,944 --> 01:07:23,647
Joe, pick me up.

713
01:08:09,908 --> 01:08:12,029
We'll be moving at daybreak.

714
01:08:12,488 --> 01:08:15,357
I'll take a few men,
see if we can find him.

715
01:08:15,524 --> 01:08:18,103
Give him a decent, Christian burial.

716
01:08:25,675 --> 01:08:28,752
Someone's coming! Someone's coning!

717
01:09:12,158 --> 01:09:14,646
Well, I can let you have
this rig for a dollar a day

718
01:09:14,677 --> 01:09:16,181
and I'll
give you a good team.

719
01:09:16,212 --> 01:09:18,250
Pick it up in the morning.
That'll be fine.

720
01:09:18,281 --> 01:09:20,401
Could you tell me the way
to the Brooks claim?

721
01:09:21,130 --> 01:09:23,584
Well, the claims are down by the river.

722
01:09:23,750 --> 01:09:27,494
Which road should I take?
Only one road. Along the river.

723
01:09:27,661 --> 01:09:29,198
Thank you.
Sure welcome.

724
01:09:43,718 --> 01:09:46,089
We're looking for a Mr. Huggins.

725
01:09:46,257 --> 01:09:48,127
You found him.

726
01:09:52,746 --> 01:09:55,574
This is Miss Lilith Prescott.

727
01:09:55,741 --> 01:09:56,988
I figured.

728
01:09:57,155 --> 01:09:59,400
They told me you was a real looker.

729
01:09:59,569 --> 01:10:03,811
Yup. It's all here for you.
Just the way Mr. Brooks staked it out.

730
01:10:03,979 --> 01:10:05,725
Must've had 20 men working on it.

731
01:10:05,892 --> 01:10:08,719
Well, where are they now?
Who's digging the gold?

732
01:10:09,095 --> 01:10:13,712
Gold? I ain't never seen a better grade
since I come here with Millie.

733
01:10:14,087 --> 01:10:15,667
It was just a pocket, though.

734
01:10:15,834 --> 01:10:19,120
The whole shebang, nothing but a pocket.

735
01:10:19,288 --> 01:10:22,947
Oh, we cleared 4200
before it played out.

736
01:10:23,115 --> 01:10:25,319
Now, about that 4200...

737
01:10:25,487 --> 01:10:27,982
Mr. Brooks, he spent three
before his heart give out.

738
01:10:28,149 --> 01:10:31,018
I put up 600 for a brass-handled casket.

739
01:10:31,186 --> 01:10:34,804
I figure the rest you owe me
for sitting on your claim.

740
01:10:38,507 --> 01:10:41,667
Oh, miss, I mean. that's
only fair, ain't it?

741
01:10:41,836 --> 01:10:44,039
I mean, wouldn't you...?

742
01:10:50,655 --> 01:10:52,816
Funny pair, all right.

743
01:11:14,826 --> 01:11:17,569
MAN: How about you boys?
Come and see the brand-mew attraction.

744
01:11:17,736 --> 01:11:20,440
It's exciting and sensational.
Step right in. gentlemen.

745
01:11:20,691 --> 01:11:23,892
(SINGING)

746
01:11:29,386 --> 01:11:31,091
(MEN LAUGHING)

747
01:12:36,988 --> 01:12:38,483
Miss Prescott?

748
01:12:38,651 --> 01:12:40,065
Hello, Mr. Morgan.

749
01:12:40,232 --> 01:12:44,765
I'd invite you in, but
it's a little cramped.

750
01:12:56,373 --> 01:12:58,535
This is no life for a fine woman like you.

751
01:13:02,197 --> 01:13:05,191
I heard your mine was played out.

752
01:13:06,191 --> 01:13:08,229
But where's your fancy friend?

753
01:13:08,395 --> 01:13:10,184
Cleve?

754
01:13:10,768 --> 01:13:14,220
Last I heard, he was in Hangtown.

755
01:13:15,094 --> 01:13:17,922
You mean that no-good went off
and left you?

756
01:13:20,585 --> 01:13:22,748
He went off and left me.

757
01:13:24,745 --> 01:13:27,541
But I don't agree that he's no good.

758
01:13:28,168 --> 01:13:30,420
Cleve is Cleve, that's all.

759
01:13:33,636 --> 01:13:36,765
You're a perplexing woman,
Miss Prescott.

760
01:13:37,434 --> 01:13:39,895
When a skunk needs killing...

761
01:13:40,231 --> 01:13:43,109
...well, it ain't enough just to say
a skunk's a skunk.

762
01:13:43,277 --> 01:13:45,029
Mr. Morgan...

763
01:13:45,657 --> 01:13:49,161
...all my life I've wanted
to marry a rich husband.

764
01:13:49,956 --> 01:13:53,628
Can I blame Cleve for wanting
to marry a rich wife?

765
01:13:55,507 --> 01:13:58,720
Both of us may have been born
for the poorhouse...

766
01:13:59,973 --> 01:14:02,518
...but we're not the kind to like it.

767
01:14:03,772 --> 01:14:06,776
Do you believe all this you've been saying,
or is it just words?

768
01:14:06,944 --> 01:14:08,069
Now, tell me the truth.

769
01:14:11,828 --> 01:14:13,745
The truth is...

770
01:14:13,913 --> 01:14:18,004
...Cleve and I couldn't live alone
just on love.

771
01:14:18,171 --> 01:14:19,756
Not for five minutes.

772
01:14:20,384 --> 01:14:25,892
Then you've answered the question I've
been asking for better than 2000 miles.

773
01:14:27,021 --> 01:14:29,356
I got the biggest ranch you ever did see.

774
01:14:29,524 --> 01:14:32,445
You can't ride across it in a day.

775
01:14:32,947 --> 01:14:36,035
That land's gonna mean money
sooner than you think.

776
01:14:37,664 --> 01:14:39,958
You want a rich husband...

777
01:14:41,253 --> 01:14:42,504
...you're looking at him.

778
01:14:50,478 --> 01:14:53,899
There ain't a blessed thing you have to do
except mind the kids.

779
01:14:57,239 --> 01:14:59,116
I'm sorry.

780
01:15:00,412 --> 01:15:02,373
Not now.

781
01:15:02,666 --> 01:15:04,335
Not ever.

782
01:15:11,682 --> 01:15:13,726
What a waste.

783
01:15:16,356 --> 01:15:18,985
Someone put together like you.

784
01:15:25,080 --> 01:15:26,748
Aggie.

785
01:15:30,297 --> 01:15:34,971
Those who struck it rich wanted
all the pleasures that money could buy.

786
01:15:35,140 --> 01:15:37,475
And there were plenty to sell to them.

787
01:15:37,643 --> 01:15:42,066
Even the Sacramento riverboats
took on luxury goods.

788
01:15:52,210 --> 01:15:55,256
(LILITH SINGING
"HOME lN THE MEADOW")

789
01:16:04,899 --> 01:16:06,818
I'll see it.

790
01:16:08,405 --> 01:16:10,283
It's up to you.

791
01:16:11,286 --> 01:16:12,912
Betting?

792
01:16:16,084 --> 01:16:18,129
What's the matter with you?

793
01:16:19,633 --> 01:16:21,343
I'm checking out.
Checking out?

794
01:16:21,512 --> 01:16:23,388
MAN:
What's the matter with him?

795
01:17:53,546 --> 01:17:56,551
Lily, I got to talk to you.

796
01:17:59,515 --> 01:18:02,729
I found myself throwing in
a winning hand.

797
01:18:02,896 --> 01:18:06,110
Well, I just never thought
I'd do that for any girl.

798
01:18:06,277 --> 01:18:07,904
Lily.

799
01:18:09,074 --> 01:18:12,245
How'd you like to hook up
with a no-good gambler?

800
01:18:17,088 --> 01:18:20,300
Oh, hon, we are on our way.
I got $1200 right here.

801
01:18:20,468 --> 01:18:22,806
What'll we do. open a gambling house?
No.

802
01:18:23,474 --> 01:18:25,685
A married man should spend
his evenings at home.

803
01:18:25,853 --> 01:18:28,023
Then we'll open a music hall
in San Francisco.

804
01:18:28,191 --> 01:18:29,692
No.
I can still sing and dance.

805
01:18:29,860 --> 01:18:32,822
No. A married woman should
spend her evenings at home.

806
01:18:32,990 --> 01:18:37,080
But we can't sit at home on $1,200 for...
Lily.

807
01:18:37,248 --> 01:18:38,305
Have you seen San Francisco?

808
01:18:39,762 --> 01:18:43,394
It's ugly, and it's small,
and it's full of fleas.

809
01:18:43,559 --> 01:18:45,624
And it burns down
about every five minutes...

810
01:18:45,790 --> 01:18:50,620
...but each time they keep on rebuilding it
a little bigger and better than before.

811
01:18:50,785 --> 01:18:54,748
It's alive and kicking
and nothing can stop it.

812
01:18:54,913 --> 01:18:57,882
And it makes you
wanna build something too.

813
01:18:58,176 --> 01:19:00,016
A railroad.

814
01:19:00,184 --> 01:19:02,317
A steamship lime.

815
01:19:02,485 --> 01:19:05,078
Something to help the baby grow.

816
01:19:05,245 --> 01:19:07,753
Cleve, on $1,200?

817
01:19:07,923 --> 01:19:11,808
We could start out
with a wagon or a rowboat.

818
01:19:11,994 --> 01:19:12,267
With the help of the devil,
I'll bet we make it.

819
01:19:40,732 --> 01:19:45,655
Young America was not only
a union of East and West.

820
01:19:45,824 --> 01:19:48,452
There were North and South too.

821
01:19:48,619 --> 01:19:51,999
And between them,
the bonds were weakening.

822
01:19:52,166 --> 01:19:55,421
Mr. Lincoln, now retired
from Congress and practicing law...

823
01:19:55,588 --> 01:19:57,881
...realized that the South would fight...

824
01:19:58,048 --> 01:20:02,220
...to mold the mew and
uncommitted territories to its own image.

825
01:20:02,472 --> 01:20:04,850
Still two years from the presidency...

826
01:20:05,019 --> 01:20:08,521
...he pleaded that the free West
be allowed to remain free...

827
01:20:08,690 --> 01:20:11,901
...and warmed of the hazards
of a house divided against itself.

828
01:20:12,778 --> 01:20:16,742
But the South,
seeing its power and influence wane...

829
01:20:16,909 --> 01:20:21,539
...struggled against the inevitable
in dozens of Western towns.

830
01:20:21,708 --> 01:20:27,087
And slowly, the bitter seeds of civil war
took root.

831
01:20:33,307 --> 01:20:35,830
(HUMMING)

832
01:21:03,951 --> 01:21:05,725
PETERSON:
Howdy, Ms. Rawlings.

833
01:21:08,371 --> 01:21:10,598
Whoa, Rosebud, whoa.

834
01:21:11,392 --> 01:21:15,366
Say. Mr. Peterson.
what's that suit you got on?

835
01:21:15,541 --> 01:21:19,858
Uniform, Mrs. Rawlings. A uniform.

836
01:21:20,031 --> 01:21:22,795
Our militia company was sworn in...

837
01:21:22,960 --> 01:21:26,713
...and I'm Corporal Peterson now,
Ohio Volunteers.

838
01:21:27,249 --> 01:21:29,886
You won't be seeing me for a spell.

839
01:21:30,465 --> 01:21:34,221
Hey, I got a letter for you.
from way out in California.

840
01:21:34,387 --> 01:21:37,111
It must be from my sister, Lilith.

841
01:21:41,116 --> 01:21:43,260
"Dear Eve..."

842
01:21:47,680 --> 01:21:50,313
Mr. Peterson, could you wait a minute?

843
01:21:50,488 --> 01:21:52,507
I wanna answer this right away.

844
01:21:52,991 --> 01:21:54,253
Zeb?

845
01:21:54,397 --> 01:21:56,409
Zeb, come on down here.

846
01:21:56,592 --> 01:22:00,634
PETERSON: Well, we was hoping
that Zeb might be going with us.

847
01:22:00,800 --> 01:22:03,839
His pa went when the first bugle blew.

848
01:22:04,008 --> 01:22:05,214
Ain't one enough?

849
01:22:06,672 --> 01:22:08,088
Hi. corporal.

850
01:22:10,172 --> 01:22:13,161
Jeremiah, get Mr. Peterson
some buttermilk.

851
01:22:13,330 --> 01:22:15,644
Buttermilk.

852
01:22:26,679 --> 01:22:28,531
It's from your aunt Lilith.

853
01:22:28,562 --> 01:22:30,334
She says there ain't no
war out in California

854
01:22:30,365 --> 01:22:32,275
and they don't expect
there'll be one.

855
01:22:33,939 --> 01:22:35,878
"Business is brisk.

856
01:22:36,043 --> 01:22:39,506
Many opportunities
for an energetic young man."

857
01:22:39,671 --> 01:22:42,888
There's talk of building a railroad east.

858
01:22:43,404 --> 01:22:46,433
"Cleve has hopes of getting in
on the ground floor.

859
01:22:47,263 --> 01:22:49,836
We would welcome Zeb
if he wants to come."

860
01:22:50,004 --> 01:22:53,904
Ma, did you write her about me?

861
01:22:54,528 --> 01:22:57,473
Not exactly.
Now, did you?

862
01:22:57,640 --> 01:23:01,333
I told her you didn't like farming
any better than your pa did.

863
01:23:01,501 --> 01:23:04,487
Ma, you got the wrong idea
about this war.

864
01:23:04,655 --> 01:23:07,392
It ain't gonna be so bad, is it, corporal?

865
01:23:07,559 --> 01:23:09,510
You know Pa's having the time of his life.

866
01:23:09,676 --> 01:23:12,456
Now, Ms. Rawlings,
I got it from the captain himself...

867
01:23:12,624 --> 01:23:16,067
...that we ain't gonna be gone
no time at all.

868
01:23:17,811 --> 01:23:20,218
Pa left it up to you whether I go or not.

869
01:23:20,385 --> 01:23:22,003
But you know what he really felt.

870
01:23:22,170 --> 01:23:25,946
Ms. Rawlings, there ain't much glory
in tromping behind a plow.

871
01:23:27,025 --> 01:23:30,677
EVE: Reckon there's no hurry
in answering this letter.

872
01:23:31,218 --> 01:23:33,167
Thank you for waiting.

873
01:23:35,410 --> 01:23:37,319
You mean I can go?

874
01:23:38,979 --> 01:23:41,635
Oh, there'll be things to do.

875
01:23:43,254 --> 01:23:44,830
Ma...

876
01:23:46,783 --> 01:23:51,306
Gotta get your underwear washed
and your socks darned.

877
01:23:53,465 --> 01:23:56,453
Do they give you one of then suits?

878
01:23:56,619 --> 01:23:59,357
One of then uniforms?

879
01:23:59,815 --> 01:24:01,889
I reckon.

880
01:24:03,219 --> 01:24:05,915
Might not give you no shirts, though.

881
01:24:06,082 --> 01:24:08,946
Take that one off, I'll wash it for you.

882
01:24:09,486 --> 01:24:12,515
I got the others washed.
They aren't ironed yet.

883
01:24:13,718 --> 01:24:15,379
Mother, I...

884
01:24:18,533 --> 01:24:20,579
Why'd you call me that?

885
01:24:20,747 --> 01:24:23,418
It's always been "Ma" before.

886
01:24:25,801 --> 01:24:27,512
I don't know.

887
01:24:28,055 --> 01:24:30,100
All of a sudden...

888
01:24:30,602 --> 01:24:33,942
...Ma didn't seen enough somehow.

889
01:24:51,105 --> 01:24:52,357
(YELLS)

890
01:24:52,526 --> 01:24:54,946
Hey, cowpoke!

891
01:25:44,515 --> 01:25:47,311
(DOG BARKING)

892
01:25:48,023 --> 01:25:50,402
ZEB:
Go on back, dog!

893
01:25:50,987 --> 01:25:52,699
Go on!

894
01:26:15,792 --> 01:26:18,130
What could I do, Pa?

895
01:26:18,298 --> 01:26:20,719
He's Linus' boy.

896
01:26:23,309 --> 01:26:26,273
Always was more Linus' blood.

897
01:26:29,322 --> 01:26:32,412
I guess that's why I love him so much.

898
01:26:37,632 --> 01:26:40,471
But you've gotta help me pray, Pa.

899
01:26:45,190 --> 01:26:47,194
Help me pray.

900
01:27:15,174 --> 01:27:17,302
(CANNONS FIRING)

901
01:27:25,070 --> 01:27:26,238
MAN 1:
Ohio.

902
01:27:26,406 --> 01:27:29,287
Battery B, Ohio!

903
01:27:29,455 --> 01:27:31,376
Let's go!
MAN 2: On the double, come on!

904
01:27:31,543 --> 01:27:35,802
MAN 3:
Anybody here from the 12th Michigan?

905
01:27:35,969 --> 01:27:39,559
MAN 4:
Thirty-sixth lndiana.

906
01:27:41,982 --> 01:27:45,949
Evening of April 6th, 1862.

907
01:27:46,158 --> 01:27:49,289
The guns that had roared all day
fell silent...

908
01:27:49,457 --> 01:27:55,052
...around a little church
called the Shiloh Meeting House.

909
01:27:55,330 --> 01:27:59,207
Many a man had met his God
that Sunday...

910
01:27:59,458 --> 01:28:01,041
...but not in church.

911
01:28:09,506 --> 01:28:11,422
You wasted your time, men. He's dead.

912
01:28:11,590 --> 01:28:15,843
But. doc, this here is Captain Rawlings.
Captain Linus Rawlings.

913
01:28:16,010 --> 01:28:18,885
Take him out.
Keep moving, men.

914
01:28:27,433 --> 01:28:31,102
Why can't you look where you're going?
I'm sorry, soldier.

915
01:28:31,270 --> 01:28:33,019
Watch it.

916
01:28:39,817 --> 01:28:42,025
Saw. Brandy.

917
01:28:42,193 --> 01:28:43,360
Chloroform.

918
01:28:44,611 --> 01:28:47,779
Get it all down. Come on, all of it.

919
01:28:49,614 --> 01:28:52,282
Come on. we're just in the way here.

920
01:28:56,619 --> 01:29:01,538
It had been the bloodiest day
of the war on the Western front.

921
01:29:01,831 --> 01:29:07,417
In the morning, it had looked like
a Confederate victory, but by nightfall...

922
01:29:07,585 --> 01:29:12,336
...no man cared to use
the words "win" or "lose."

923
01:29:14,047 --> 01:29:16,423
After Shiloh...

924
01:29:17,257 --> 01:29:20,133
...the South never smiled.

925
01:29:34,143 --> 01:29:36,102
You tasted that water yet?
No.

926
01:29:36,269 --> 01:29:38,145
Well, try it.

927
01:29:43,107 --> 01:29:45,107
Tastes funny, huh?
Yeah.

928
01:29:45,275 --> 01:29:47,984
I seen it before sundown. It was pink.

929
01:29:48,152 --> 01:29:50,652
Pinker than sassafras tea.

930
01:29:50,820 --> 01:29:51,945
You mean...?

931
01:29:52,113 --> 01:29:55,114
It don't seen fitting a nan should have
to drink water like that.

932
01:29:55,282 --> 01:29:58,866
Don't seen fitting a man should have
to do any of the things we've dome today.

933
01:29:59,034 --> 01:30:01,826
Did you kill anybody?

934
01:30:01,994 --> 01:30:04,161
I don't think so.

935
01:30:04,537 --> 01:30:07,204
I got knocked dizzy right off.

936
01:30:08,040 --> 01:30:12,333
And when I come to, found my rifle,
it was busted.

937
01:30:13,585 --> 01:30:18,295
And then some more soldiers come along
and tried to stick me in the arm.

938
01:30:20,048 --> 01:30:22,840
All the rest is nixed up after that.

939
01:30:23,008 --> 01:30:27,176
Well, I ain't killed nobody, neither.
And I don't want to.

940
01:30:28,261 --> 01:30:31,637
Hey, where you from?
Ohio.

941
01:30:31,804 --> 01:30:35,598
This fool war started in the East.
What's us Westerners doing in it?

942
01:30:35,766 --> 01:30:38,975
I don't rightly know anymore.

943
01:30:43,228 --> 01:30:45,771
It ain't quite what I expected.

944
01:30:47,565 --> 01:30:52,567
There ain't much glory looking at a man
with his guts hanging out.

945
01:30:55,195 --> 01:30:58,029
Where are you from?
Texas.

946
01:30:59,530 --> 01:31:01,114
Say...

947
01:31:01,449 --> 01:31:03,407
You ain't a Reb, are you?

948
01:31:03,575 --> 01:31:08,285
Well, I was this morning.
Tonight, I ain't so sure.

949
01:31:08,745 --> 01:31:12,580
Seems like I ought to be shooting you.

950
01:31:13,414 --> 01:31:16,666
Well, you got anything to shoot with?

951
01:31:18,418 --> 01:31:20,043
No.

952
01:31:20,211 --> 01:31:22,711
All I got's this bayonet.

953
01:31:23,213 --> 01:31:25,380
I got a pistol.

954
01:31:26,256 --> 01:31:29,299
I took it off a dead officer.

955
01:31:32,094 --> 01:31:35,053
Hey, why don't we
skedaddle out of here?

956
01:31:35,762 --> 01:31:37,846
You mean desert?
I mean. why don't...?

957
01:31:38,013 --> 01:31:41,598
Just leave this here war
to the folks who'd want it.

958
01:31:46,727 --> 01:31:50,729
They say there ain't no war
out in California.

959
01:31:51,939 --> 01:31:54,648
MAN:
Get that battery over here.

960
01:31:57,026 --> 01:32:02,028
Stragglers, join your regiment.
Stragglers. Hey, you!

961
01:32:10,576 --> 01:32:13,910
I'm planning to move Rousseau's brigade
into this area.

962
01:32:14,578 --> 01:32:19,248
Hidden battery, placed well before dawn.
Do you approve?

963
01:32:19,415 --> 01:32:22,416
I'll approve any dispositions
you wanna make.

964
01:32:22,583 --> 01:32:26,752
If you hadn't held the flank today,
we'd have been whipped for fair.

965
01:32:27,295 --> 01:32:31,672
Sherman. let's sit down a minute.
There's something I wanna say to you.

966
01:32:33,382 --> 01:32:35,299
Lantern.

967
01:32:40,929 --> 01:32:43,096
GRANT:
You may find yourself in command here.

968
01:32:43,264 --> 01:32:44,346
SHERMAN:
Why?

969
01:32:44,973 --> 01:32:50,892
I've seen some of the dispatches the
newspaper correspondents have filed today.

970
01:32:51,060 --> 01:32:54,186
They're saying
I was taken by surprise this morning.

971
01:32:54,354 --> 01:32:57,022
You weren't taken by surprise.

972
01:32:57,189 --> 01:32:58,439
I was.

973
01:32:58,606 --> 01:33:00,357
GRANT:
No matter.

974
01:33:00,734 --> 01:33:01,858
They're saying...

975
01:33:03,651 --> 01:33:06,319
...I was drunk again last night.

976
01:33:09,031 --> 01:33:10,697
SHERMAN:
Were you?

977
01:33:13,116 --> 01:33:14,616
No.

978
01:33:15,284 --> 01:33:18,243
But you can't fight front and rear.

979
01:33:18,411 --> 01:33:20,661
Win or lose, tomorrow...

980
01:33:21,621 --> 01:33:23,288
...I intend to resign.

981
01:33:24,999 --> 01:33:27,666
SHERMAN:
Because of the newspapers?

982
01:33:29,668 --> 01:33:32,794
Because of a general
lack of confidence in me.

983
01:33:32,962 --> 01:33:36,088
Oh, don't you think
I've ever felt like that?

984
01:33:36,256 --> 01:33:39,840
A month ago they were saying
I was crazy. Insane.

985
01:33:40,008 --> 01:33:44,469
Now they're calling me a hero.
A hero or crazy, I'm the same man.

986
01:33:44,636 --> 01:33:47,012
It doesn't matter what the people think.

987
01:33:47,180 --> 01:33:48,763
It's what you think, Grant.

988
01:33:51,891 --> 01:33:53,891
You mean that's Grant?

989
01:33:55,852 --> 01:33:57,310
I reckon.

990
01:33:57,478 --> 01:33:59,644
General Grant.

991
01:33:59,812 --> 01:34:03,355
You know this war's gonna be won
in the West, and how to win it.

992
01:34:03,523 --> 01:34:06,066
Everything you've dome proves it.

993
01:34:06,734 --> 01:34:11,944
And I say that a nan has the right
to resign only if he's wrong.

994
01:34:12,237 --> 01:34:14,237
Not if he's right.

995
01:34:15,822 --> 01:34:20,450
I guess I never thought of it that way.

996
01:34:21,367 --> 01:34:22,576
I'll think it over.

997
01:34:23,495 --> 01:34:24,994
SHERMAN:
What is there to think about?

998
01:34:25,162 --> 01:34:29,371
The Army's better off with you
than without you. That's the test.

999
01:34:33,042 --> 01:34:34,751
All right.

1000
01:34:35,168 --> 01:34:36,335
Thanks.

1001
01:34:38,212 --> 01:34:41,129
There's a lot to do
before morning, Sherman.

1002
01:34:41,297 --> 01:34:42,339
ZEB:
What are you doing?

1003
01:34:42,507 --> 01:34:43,923
(GUNSHOT)

1004
01:34:44,341 --> 01:34:47,300
(CHATTERING AND HOOVES PATTERING)

1005
01:35:00,976 --> 01:35:03,310
Why did you make me do that?

1006
01:35:51,425 --> 01:35:53,134
MAN:
Fire.

1007
01:37:33,324 --> 01:37:35,282
Hey, Zeb!

1008
01:38:00,466 --> 01:38:02,633
Didn't you get my letter?

1009
01:38:03,801 --> 01:38:06,469
I wrote more than four months ago.

1010
01:38:09,096 --> 01:38:10,846
She never was...

1011
01:38:11,014 --> 01:38:15,141
...quite the same
after she got the mews about Pa.

1012
01:38:18,269 --> 01:38:21,479
I don't think she minded going.
Zeb, except...

1013
01:38:23,105 --> 01:38:25,397
...she wanted to see you again.

1014
01:38:30,235 --> 01:38:33,236
Of course Pa ain't really there.

1015
01:38:35,613 --> 01:38:37,948
I put up a stone anyway.

1016
01:38:57,086 --> 01:38:58,669
Well...

1017
01:38:59,337 --> 01:39:01,462
...better be on my way.

1018
01:39:02,005 --> 01:39:04,506
Way? Where?

1019
01:39:04,674 --> 01:39:06,590
I meed you, Zeb.

1020
01:39:06,758 --> 01:39:09,217
Only one thing brought me back.

1021
01:39:10,344 --> 01:39:12,302
She's...

1022
01:39:12,470 --> 01:39:14,762
Well, this farm is half yours.

1023
01:39:14,930 --> 01:39:19,516
I was thinking we'd finally clear away that
patch of woods down by the river and...

1024
01:39:19,683 --> 01:39:23,351
You're twice the farmer I an.
You don't meed me.

1025
01:39:23,519 --> 01:39:27,145
Farm's all yours. It's only fair.

1026
01:39:28,522 --> 01:39:31,314
Sure don't feel right about this.

1027
01:39:31,482 --> 01:39:32,983
What are you gonna do?

1028
01:39:33,150 --> 01:39:34,817
I haven't mustered out yet.

1029
01:39:34,985 --> 01:39:37,110
I can still transfer to the regulars.

1030
01:39:37,278 --> 01:39:40,362
Cavalry, maybe. Go west.

1031
01:39:40,530 --> 01:39:43,030
Have to fight Indians?

1032
01:39:43,865 --> 01:39:46,241
You sure are hard to make out. Zeb.

1033
01:39:46,409 --> 01:39:50,410
Now, what do you wanna do that for?
Do you like fighting?

1034
01:39:51,704 --> 01:39:55,871
You remember the story Pa used to tell us
about fighting that grizzly bear?

1035
01:39:56,039 --> 01:39:57,123
Yeah.

1036
01:39:57,291 --> 01:40:00,542
And I asked him, I said.
"Well. why'd you get in such a fix?

1037
01:40:00,710 --> 01:40:03,127
Do you like fighting grizzlies?"

1038
01:40:03,295 --> 01:40:04,836
He said:

1039
01:40:05,004 --> 01:40:09,339
(IMITATING RAWLINGS)
"Well. uh. not especially. Uh...

1040
01:40:09,548 --> 01:40:14,050
I just wanted to go somewhere
and the bear was there first."

1041
01:40:26,600 --> 01:40:28,226
(IN NORMAL VOICE)
Well, I...

1042
01:40:31,187 --> 01:40:33,980
I guess I just wanna go somewhere too.

1043
01:40:38,233 --> 01:40:41,693
So long.
So long, Zeb.

1044
01:41:00,873 --> 01:41:04,166
Even while North and South
were being torn apart...

1045
01:41:04,334 --> 01:41:08,209
...East and West had been
drawn together by the Pony Express...

1046
01:41:08,377 --> 01:41:10,794
...the most daring mail route in history.

1047
01:41:10,962 --> 01:41:14,630
Eighty riders were in the saddle at all
times, night and day, in all weather.

1048
01:41:14,798 --> 01:41:17,591
Half of them riding east,
half riding west...

1049
01:41:17,759 --> 01:41:19,884
...between Missouri and Sacramento...

1050
01:41:20,052 --> 01:41:24,094
...carrying mail across country
in days instead of months.

1051
01:41:24,262 --> 01:41:27,055
Unarmed, they rode to save weight.

1052
01:41:27,222 --> 01:41:30,891
Five dollars a letter, the mail cost,
and on thin paper too.

1053
01:41:31,059 --> 01:41:34,018
It was courage, skill and speed...

1054
01:41:34,186 --> 01:41:39,688
...against hostile Indians, bandits,
hell and occasional high water.

1055
01:41:40,231 --> 01:41:42,648
Even as they rode,
men were already building...

1056
01:41:42,816 --> 01:41:47,610
...a faster message carrier across
the country: the Overland Telegraph.

1057
01:41:47,778 --> 01:41:50,278
And the Indians found
a mew amusement...

1058
01:41:50,446 --> 01:41:53,614
...listening to the level tune
of the singing wires.

1059
01:41:53,782 --> 01:41:55,907
But far less amusing to the Indians...

1060
01:41:56,075 --> 01:41:59,951
...was the coming of the steel roadway
of the iron horse.

1061
01:42:00,118 --> 01:42:06,121
The surveyors' route lay through immense
natural barriers, the Rocky Mountains...

1062
01:42:06,289 --> 01:42:09,540
...and the equally discouraging
High Sierras.

1063
01:42:09,708 --> 01:42:13,627
But range upon range could never stop
the titanic contest...

1064
01:42:13,794 --> 01:42:16,295
...between two corporate giants
racing to put down...

1065
01:42:16,463 --> 01:42:19,797
...the greatest mileage of track
before they met.

1066
01:42:19,964 --> 01:42:24,759
The Central Pacific eastward
from Sacramento through the Sierras.

1067
01:42:28,595 --> 01:42:32,680
And the Union Pacific,
forging westward across the plains...

1068
01:42:32,848 --> 01:42:34,723
...with the Rockies still to come.

1069
01:42:34,891 --> 01:42:40,435
The prize in the race was free land,
vast parcels for every mile of track laid.

1070
01:42:40,603 --> 01:42:44,021
Land that would one day
be worth millions.

1071
01:42:49,192 --> 01:42:50,983
MAN 1:
Hold it.

1072
01:42:51,151 --> 01:42:52,943
Set it down.

1073
01:42:53,486 --> 01:42:55,653
Workers, up.

1074
01:43:01,658 --> 01:43:03,283
MAN 2:
Where'd you find them?

1075
01:43:03,451 --> 01:43:05,868
MAN 3:
About a mile back yonder.

1076
01:43:06,327 --> 01:43:09,787
MAN 4: That's Johnny Hormatz.
MAN 5: That's Jack Perkin.

1077
01:43:11,956 --> 01:43:13,832
KING:
What the hell is this? A picnic?

1078
01:43:13,999 --> 01:43:16,014
Well, the Indians got
a couple of our men...

1079
01:43:16,045 --> 01:43:17,808
Mister, you were
the foreman here.

1080
01:43:17,839 --> 01:43:20,919
Now you're a track-layer.
Now get back to work. all of you!

1081
01:43:21,087 --> 01:43:22,462
Move it!

1082
01:43:22,630 --> 01:43:24,255
Fast!

1083
01:43:24,423 --> 01:43:25,548
You.
Yes, sir.

1084
01:43:25,714 --> 01:43:28,049
You're the foreman
till I can find somebody better.

1085
01:43:28,217 --> 01:43:29,550
Yes, sir.
Get then at it.

1086
01:43:29,717 --> 01:43:31,676
Wait a minute.
Move it!

1087
01:43:31,844 --> 01:43:34,594
Your name Jethro Stuart?

1088
01:43:34,887 --> 01:43:36,179
MAN:
All right. get at it.

1089
01:43:36,347 --> 01:43:39,973
Well, Mr. Jethro Stuart, you're hired
to hunt buffalo to feed these men...

1090
01:43:40,141 --> 01:43:43,684
...not to stop their work.
Why'd you bring these bodies here?

1091
01:43:43,852 --> 01:43:46,978
They're railroaders. I thought somebody
in the railroad night be interested.

1092
01:43:47,146 --> 01:43:50,021
I'm the railroad and I'm not interested.

1093
01:43:50,189 --> 01:43:53,440
You should've buried them,
then tracked down the Indians who did it.

1094
01:43:54,400 --> 01:43:56,900
Well, Mr. King, like you said.
I was hired to hunt...

1095
01:43:57,068 --> 01:44:00,194
...not to dig graves or fight Indians.

1096
01:44:00,362 --> 01:44:02,070
Those fellas are mostly old soldiers.

1097
01:44:02,238 --> 01:44:04,738
You wouldn't think a couple
dead men bother them much.

1098
01:44:04,906 --> 01:44:08,783
I don't want anything in their thick skulls
but their work. Do you understand?

1099
01:44:08,951 --> 01:44:11,994
Now, get rid of those bodies.
Start tracking those Indians.

1100
01:44:12,162 --> 01:44:16,872
You keep forgetting, Mr. King,
my job's buffalo.

1101
01:44:18,832 --> 01:44:20,666
It was buffalo.

1102
01:44:20,834 --> 01:44:23,209
Go to the paymaster and draw your time.

1103
01:44:23,377 --> 01:44:25,794
Well, now. that foreman fella,
you didn't fire him.

1104
01:44:25,962 --> 01:44:28,754
You just took him down a peg
because you needed him.

1105
01:44:28,922 --> 01:44:30,881
Who's gonna shoot buffalo? You?

1106
01:44:31,507 --> 01:44:33,215
(PIANO PLAYING)

1107
01:44:33,633 --> 01:44:35,508
(CHATTERING)

1108
01:45:03,402 --> 01:45:06,069
What the devil is that?
Milk.

1109
01:45:06,237 --> 01:45:08,070
Milk?

1110
01:45:08,405 --> 01:45:10,947
The Army must've changed
since I was in it.

1111
01:45:11,115 --> 01:45:14,909
Just rode in. I'm hungry.
You are. huh?

1112
01:45:15,744 --> 01:45:18,244
But you'd rather watch them than eat.

1113
01:45:18,412 --> 01:45:20,078
Is that it?
That's it.

1114
01:45:20,246 --> 01:45:23,664
Well, I wish you were as eager
to protect this railroad.

1115
01:45:23,832 --> 01:45:26,917
Did you get any word about those two men
who were killed today?

1116
01:45:27,084 --> 01:45:30,126
I tracked the Arapahos
and talked to the chief.

1117
01:45:30,294 --> 01:45:32,378
Those men were a mile off
the right-of-way...

1118
01:45:32,546 --> 01:45:35,630
...where they had no business,
drunk and chasing squaws.

1119
01:45:35,797 --> 01:45:37,669
As much their fault as
it was the Indians'.

1120
01:45:37,700 --> 01:45:38,812
Is that a fact?

1121
01:45:39,675 --> 01:45:44,010
Well, soldier boy, your job is to fight
Indians, not to agree with then.

1122
01:45:44,178 --> 01:45:48,639
Mr. King, there were 200 Arapahos
and I had 20 men.

1123
01:45:48,806 --> 01:45:50,556
Now, to me...

1124
01:45:50,724 --> 01:45:52,766
...agreeing seemed wiser than fighting.

1125
01:45:52,934 --> 01:45:54,893
To you, huh?

1126
01:45:55,060 --> 01:45:58,686
Well, you know, I might just send off
a wire to the colonel.

1127
01:45:58,938 --> 01:46:01,104
He may not agree.

1128
01:46:02,148 --> 01:46:04,899
I already reported. He does agree.

1129
01:46:24,371 --> 01:46:27,580
(BOTH SPEAKING
IN NATIVE LANGUAGE)

1130
01:46:38,088 --> 01:46:40,880
Acknowledged and understood. Sergeant.

1131
01:46:41,048 --> 01:46:42,464
Trouble. sir?

1132
01:46:47,969 --> 01:46:49,469
I don't know.

1133
01:46:49,637 --> 01:46:51,470
STUART:
Hey, lieutenant.

1134
01:46:53,556 --> 01:46:55,640
I got a message:
Indians are up to something.

1135
01:46:55,807 --> 01:46:57,558
You know anything about it?

1136
01:46:57,892 --> 01:47:00,476
Chief says railroad busted the agreement.

1137
01:47:00,644 --> 01:47:03,979
Changed the route. come snack
through Arapaho hunting grounds.

1138
01:47:04,145 --> 01:47:06,564
You sure the chief's right?
Plenty sure.

1139
01:47:06,731 --> 01:47:08,982
They're getting the war paint ready.

1140
01:47:12,693 --> 01:47:14,569
Can you stand there and tell me...

1141
01:47:14,903 --> 01:47:18,612
...that one little change is gonna cost
the Arapahos one buffalo.

1142
01:47:18,780 --> 01:47:21,114
Or even one jackrabbit?
Mr. King.

1143
01:47:21,282 --> 01:47:24,616
They can be made to see it differently.
Who's hurting then?

1144
01:47:24,784 --> 01:47:27,827
What's a railroad anyway?
Two tracks and a whistle.

1145
01:47:28,662 --> 01:47:32,121
It's not the tracks they're afraid of.
It's what the tracks bring.

1146
01:47:32,289 --> 01:47:35,123
The buffalo hunters slaughtering off
their herds.

1147
01:47:35,291 --> 01:47:36,958
And then the settlers coning in.

1148
01:47:37,126 --> 01:47:40,002
And when will that be?
Twenty, 30 years, maybe?

1149
01:47:40,168 --> 01:47:42,336
By then. we'll all be dead.

1150
01:47:42,504 --> 01:47:44,671
Right now we're just crossing the land.

1151
01:47:44,839 --> 01:47:48,506
That's all. Land that's safe
to the Arapahos for our lifetime.

1152
01:47:48,674 --> 01:47:49,841
Now, you go talk to then.

1153
01:47:50,009 --> 01:47:52,968
Smoke a peace pipe with then.
Do anything they want.

1154
01:47:53,136 --> 01:47:55,344
Just get them to make a mew agreement.

1155
01:47:57,221 --> 01:48:00,431
That's your job. isn't it?
Keeping the peace?

1156
01:48:02,142 --> 01:48:04,267
I'll keep the peace. Mr. King...

1157
01:48:04,435 --> 01:48:06,810
...but you keep your promise.

1158
01:48:15,317 --> 01:48:17,358
Hear your name's Rawlings,
you're from Ohio.

1159
01:48:17,526 --> 01:48:20,861
Your pa's name couldn't be
Linus Rawlings, could it?

1160
01:48:21,029 --> 01:48:22,695
Could be.
Knew him.

1161
01:48:22,863 --> 01:48:24,238
Jethro Stuart.

1162
01:48:24,405 --> 01:48:27,032
He used to speak of you.
Used to?

1163
01:48:27,198 --> 01:48:29,408
Pa was killed at Shiloh.

1164
01:48:30,075 --> 01:48:32,368
Sit down, Mr. Stuart.

1165
01:48:33,369 --> 01:48:35,120
Well, better than dying behind a plow.

1166
01:48:35,912 --> 01:48:39,205
I tried it. Settled down for a year once.

1167
01:48:39,373 --> 01:48:41,540
Took 10 years off my life.

1168
01:48:44,001 --> 01:48:45,710
Your ma...

1169
01:48:46,170 --> 01:48:50,963
She must've been something real special
getting old Linus to stay put.

1170
01:48:51,131 --> 01:48:54,715
She was, Mr. Stuart. Very special.

1171
01:48:54,883 --> 01:48:56,550
Old Linus.

1172
01:48:56,718 --> 01:48:59,095
Two years running once.
Your pa and me trapped together.

1173
01:48:59,126 --> 01:49:01,043
Up along the Waumakee.

1174
01:49:01,512 --> 01:49:04,055
Got so many beaver,
we had to tie them tail-to-tail...

1175
01:49:04,222 --> 01:49:06,139
...just to drag them down the mountain.

1176
01:49:06,307 --> 01:49:09,391
Over a mile long it was,
that lime of beaver pelts.

1177
01:49:09,559 --> 01:49:13,895
Mr. Stuart, my father could take the truth
and stretch it about six ways.

1178
01:49:14,062 --> 01:49:16,146
You sound just like him.

1179
01:49:17,105 --> 01:49:19,648
I'll take it you meant that kindly.

1180
01:49:19,815 --> 01:49:22,858
Well, I'd think twice
before I called you a liar.

1181
01:49:23,026 --> 01:49:25,777
Tell me something.
talking about liars.

1182
01:49:25,944 --> 01:49:30,696
Why would a son of old Linus
get mixed up with a man like Mike King?

1183
01:49:31,573 --> 01:49:33,074
I know what you mean.

1184
01:49:33,241 --> 01:49:36,241
But Mike King isn't the railroad.
Oh?

1185
01:49:36,409 --> 01:49:38,577
I don't think he knows that.

1186
01:49:38,745 --> 01:49:41,204
He's changing the route back, is he?

1187
01:49:41,372 --> 01:49:42,829
No.

1188
01:49:43,748 --> 01:49:44,747
I know.

1189
01:49:44,915 --> 01:49:47,916
But he'd do anything
to gain a day on the Central Pacific.

1190
01:49:48,084 --> 01:49:52,711
He's not a fool. He doesn't want a war,
and neither do the Arapahos.

1191
01:49:53,420 --> 01:49:56,254
I think I could get then to agree
to this change in route...

1192
01:49:56,422 --> 01:49:58,589
...if I sit down and talk with then
for a while.

1193
01:49:58,757 --> 01:50:01,424
How you gonna get them to do it?
That's just it.

1194
01:50:01,592 --> 01:50:04,885
I meed somebody that knows
the language and who they trust.

1195
01:50:06,096 --> 01:50:09,471
You wouldn't happen to know someone
like that, would you, Mr. Stuart?

1196
01:50:12,516 --> 01:50:16,976
Your pa could set a trap
like no nan I ever come across.

1197
01:50:17,144 --> 01:50:20,145
Just coax then on and, ban.

1198
01:50:21,355 --> 01:50:24,773
(SPEAKING IN NATIVE LANGUAGE)

1199
01:50:37,281 --> 01:50:40,783
STUART: You'd better do something
so he'll know you're pledging your word.

1200
01:51:18,100 --> 01:51:21,434
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

1201
01:51:24,019 --> 01:51:25,520
(GROANS)

1202
01:51:26,731 --> 01:51:31,149
That blame whistle's like the crack of doom
for all that's natural.

1203
01:51:31,316 --> 01:51:34,568
My ma felt a man ought to
make his scratch on the land.

1204
01:51:34,736 --> 01:51:37,695
Leave it a little different
than when he come.

1205
01:51:37,862 --> 01:51:40,530
Anyway, thanks for fixing things
with the chief.

1206
01:51:40,697 --> 01:51:42,156
Me? I fixed nothing.

1207
01:51:42,323 --> 01:51:45,324
You put the words to my mouth
but that won't make then come true.

1208
01:51:45,492 --> 01:51:47,951
Jethro, I said what I had to
to keep the peace.

1209
01:51:48,119 --> 01:51:50,077
I know there's a risk.
Risk?

1210
01:51:50,245 --> 01:51:52,245
Maybe you don't understand.

1211
01:51:52,413 --> 01:51:53,997
You pledged your word back there.

1212
01:51:54,165 --> 01:51:56,665
Not mime, not the Army's,
not the railroad's.

1213
01:51:56,833 --> 01:51:59,542
It's your word told then
they'd keep their hunting grounds.

1214
01:51:59,710 --> 01:52:02,419
I think they will.
I think you got your neck stuck out...

1215
01:52:02,587 --> 01:52:06,213
...like a prairie chicken waiting for
one side or the other to chop it off.

1216
01:52:06,381 --> 01:52:09,299
Your pa and me got kicked out
of one territory after another...

1217
01:52:09,467 --> 01:52:12,885
...with people pouring in,
killing off game, putting up towns.

1218
01:52:13,052 --> 01:52:14,845
It ain't gonna stop.

1219
01:52:15,013 --> 01:52:18,973
Your treaty's gonna get broke and
I don't wanna be around to see it happen.

1220
01:52:19,515 --> 01:52:21,808
Look me up when you get your bellyful.

1221
01:52:21,976 --> 01:52:24,226
Where you going?
Heading back to the mountains.

1222
01:52:24,394 --> 01:52:28,313
A high lonesome
where there ain't no people at all yet.

1223
01:52:28,564 --> 01:52:30,314
So long.

1224
01:52:37,361 --> 01:52:41,489
By now, the Central Pacific had broken
through the wall of the high Sierras...

1225
01:52:41,656 --> 01:52:46,117
...and was straining eastward
across the flatland's of Nevada.

1226
01:52:46,285 --> 01:52:50,078
While the Union Pacific, thanks to
its long peace with the Indians...

1227
01:52:50,246 --> 01:52:54,956
...was able to keep up pressure
just as avidly in the opposite direction.

1228
01:53:09,635 --> 01:53:13,136
The competition was exciting,
but also costly...

1229
01:53:13,304 --> 01:53:18,515
...and both companies were itching
to earn money from tracks already laid.

1230
01:53:19,642 --> 01:53:21,059
(MAN SPEAKING IN FRENCH)

1231
01:53:21,227 --> 01:53:23,185
(CHATTERING)

1232
01:53:32,192 --> 01:53:34,944
MAN: Did the horses ride all right, Jake?
No better than I did.

1233
01:53:35,110 --> 01:53:39,071
We'll have to rest them a day before we can
start hunting rabbits, much less buffalo.

1234
01:53:39,239 --> 01:53:41,365
MAN:
Just get them to water right away.

1235
01:53:41,533 --> 01:53:43,741
You say no buffalo hunter come.

1236
01:53:43,909 --> 01:53:45,534
White man, liar.

1237
01:53:45,701 --> 01:53:48,370
We scout for you no more.

1238
01:53:54,208 --> 01:53:55,791
Not in our lifetime. you said.

1239
01:53:55,959 --> 01:54:00,086
And there they are.
The buffalo slaughterers and the settlers.

1240
01:54:00,254 --> 01:54:02,879
All right. it's sooner than I figured.

1241
01:54:03,047 --> 01:54:06,257
But the railroad's broke.
They meed money to keep moving on.

1242
01:54:06,424 --> 01:54:08,717
No people, no money.
No money, no railroad.

1243
01:54:08,885 --> 01:54:11,511
It's as simple as that.
What about the Arapahos?

1244
01:54:11,679 --> 01:54:15,556
Just take a look at those people.
Half of them straight from Europe.

1245
01:54:15,723 --> 01:54:17,849
They'll have a rough time.
but they'll make it.

1246
01:54:18,016 --> 01:54:19,933
And do you wanna know
why they'll make it?

1247
01:54:20,101 --> 01:54:23,561
Because they're willing
to change their ways.

1248
01:54:23,728 --> 01:54:26,771
Arapahos will have to change too.
If they don't, they're finished.

1249
01:54:26,939 --> 01:54:29,816
I know they have to
and someday the land will be taken over...

1250
01:54:29,984 --> 01:54:32,526
...by these farmers
with their towns and their cattle.

1251
01:54:32,694 --> 01:54:33,901
But not like this.

1252
01:54:34,069 --> 01:54:37,487
They don't have to be double-crossed,
and I don't have to be a part of it.

1253
01:54:37,655 --> 01:54:39,906
You don't, lieutenant?

1254
01:54:40,074 --> 01:54:42,283
Well, aren't you forgetting that uniform?

1255
01:54:42,450 --> 01:54:44,659
That's right, Mr. King, I'm forgetting it.

1256
01:54:44,827 --> 01:54:48,120
If the Army hasn't got any authority
out here. I'm resigning. And now.

1257
01:54:48,288 --> 01:54:50,455
I don't see how that's
gonna help the Arapahos.

1258
01:54:50,623 --> 01:54:51,956
Nothing will help then.

1259
01:54:52,124 --> 01:54:54,833
But nothing's gonna stop them.

1260
01:55:21,853 --> 01:55:23,812
(GUNSHOTS)

1261
01:55:25,023 --> 01:55:26,772
ZEB:
Indian attack!

1262
01:55:26,940 --> 01:55:28,690
Indian attack! Take cover!

1263
01:55:39,490 --> 01:55:40,866
Take a good look.

1264
01:55:41,034 --> 01:55:44,744
You wanted a war and you got one.
I hope you're the first nan killed in it.

1265
01:55:44,912 --> 01:55:47,370
Turn those wagons over!

1266
01:56:09,054 --> 01:56:11,179
ZEB: Shoot for the lead horses.
Pick off the chief.

1267
01:56:11,347 --> 01:56:13,555
Rawlings. try that.

1268
01:56:22,897 --> 01:56:25,022
MAN:
The Indians are stampeding the buffalo.

1269
01:56:25,190 --> 01:56:27,690
Dirty skunks. Come on.

1270
01:56:33,863 --> 01:56:36,030
(GUNSHOTS)

1271
01:58:44,289 --> 01:58:47,623
I told you there'd be no war.

1272
01:58:47,791 --> 01:58:49,249
Look at then.

1273
01:58:49,417 --> 01:58:51,500
They've quit.

1274
01:58:51,668 --> 01:58:53,794
They'll be back.

1275
01:58:54,171 --> 01:58:58,756
They just sent a bunch of animals to kill
an animal they call the "iron horse."

1276
01:58:58,923 --> 01:59:01,300
Well, it's still standing, isn't it?

1277
01:59:01,468 --> 01:59:03,551
And nothing's gonna stop it.

1278
01:59:03,719 --> 01:59:06,219
(CHILD CRYING)

1279
01:59:23,566 --> 01:59:26,317
You think you can live with that?

1280
01:59:26,943 --> 01:59:29,402
I can live with it, or I can die with it.

1281
01:59:29,570 --> 01:59:31,404
Just listen.

1282
01:59:31,572 --> 01:59:33,989
You can live with that?

1283
01:59:34,657 --> 01:59:35,824
That?

1284
01:59:35,992 --> 01:59:37,742
That ain't crying.

1285
01:59:37,910 --> 01:59:40,827
That's just mew life going on.

1286
01:59:46,083 --> 01:59:50,000
MAN: Pick up this woman and put the rest
of the injured in the tent house.

1287
01:59:54,505 --> 01:59:55,505
Hey, Merv...

1288
01:59:55,672 --> 01:59:58,757
KING: The rest of you. back to work.
We got a railroad to build.

1289
02:00:14,018 --> 02:00:15,602
(WHISTLE BLOWS)

1290
02:00:39,703 --> 02:00:41,703
(HORSE WHINNIES)

1291
02:00:51,962 --> 02:00:53,712
Well...

1292
02:00:54,214 --> 02:00:56,548
Looks like you finally got your bellyful.

1293
02:00:56,715 --> 02:00:58,632
Hello, Jethro.

1294
02:00:59,175 --> 02:01:01,343
Appears you're doing well.

1295
02:01:02,052 --> 02:01:03,886
Can't complain.

1296
02:01:04,054 --> 02:01:08,265
Creek's loaded with beavers,
fighting their way into the trap.

1297
02:01:08,432 --> 02:01:10,307
No white men looking
over my shoulder...

1298
02:01:10,475 --> 02:01:13,059
...and the Indians are plumb cordial.

1299
02:01:13,227 --> 02:01:16,061
Toss your stuff in there.
Plenty of room for two.

1300
02:01:16,229 --> 02:01:17,729
Thanks.

1301
02:01:18,982 --> 02:01:20,148
You'll be bunking yonder.

1302
02:01:20,315 --> 02:01:23,066
Take your bearings now
so you can find it when you meed it.

1303
02:01:23,234 --> 02:01:26,110
If you don't like my snoring,
you can build your own cabin.

1304
02:01:26,278 --> 02:01:28,445
I'll furnish the ax.

1305
02:01:29,989 --> 02:01:33,365
Thanks. I'm just passing through.
Through to where?

1306
02:01:33,533 --> 02:01:35,659
Anywhere you go is like
where you've been.

1307
02:01:35,827 --> 02:01:38,077
Ain't you lost enough tail feathers
back there?

1308
02:01:40,121 --> 02:01:42,205
I've been plucked some.

1309
02:01:43,124 --> 02:01:45,082
But that's what I like about this country.

1310
02:01:45,250 --> 02:01:48,209
There's always greener grass
over the next hill.

1311
02:01:48,377 --> 02:01:51,211
Not no more.
Not since that damn railroad come.

1312
02:01:51,379 --> 02:01:54,922
All the grass is being staked out now.
with a lock on it.

1313
02:01:57,091 --> 02:02:00,676
Maybe I'll just have to climb
a little higher hill to find it.

1314
02:02:03,597 --> 02:02:05,096
How about coning along?

1315
02:02:05,264 --> 02:02:07,347
You crazy?

1316
02:02:07,515 --> 02:02:11,267
Like the Indians say, "These rocks and
trees around here feel no call to move."

1317
02:02:11,435 --> 02:02:13,019
Why should I?

1318
02:02:14,104 --> 02:02:16,438
Guess I'm not an Indian. Jethro.

1319
02:02:16,606 --> 02:02:19,440
But I'm sure not a rock nor a tree.

1320
02:02:19,608 --> 02:02:22,775
Man belongs his own kind,
like him or not.

1321
02:02:58,886 --> 02:03:03,137
The coming of railroads brought changes
in the land through which they passed.

1322
02:03:03,305 --> 02:03:06,973
Now immense herds of cattle were driven
hundreds of miles to meet the limes...

1323
02:03:07,141 --> 02:03:08,975
...bound for markets in the East.

1324
02:03:09,517 --> 02:03:12,685
Fences went up, cattle
trails were barred...

1325
02:03:12,978 --> 02:03:16,730
...and a long and bloody wrangle began
between cattlemen and homesteaders.

1326
02:03:17,315 --> 02:03:21,400
The law was in the hands of whoever
could shoot fast and straight...

1327
02:03:21,568 --> 02:03:25,779
...except where there was somebody
determined to stand for law.

1328
02:03:25,947 --> 02:03:29,698
Others might look on sheep and a shepherd
as a pastoral scene.

1329
02:03:29,865 --> 02:03:31,783
(GUNSHOT)

1330
02:03:32,409 --> 02:03:33,867
Not the cattleman.

1331
02:03:34,035 --> 02:03:39,622
To him, sheep destroyed grass,
and grass came dear.

1332
02:03:39,790 --> 02:03:42,415
And if a man's life were held cheaper
than grass...

1333
02:03:42,583 --> 02:03:46,585
...it was considered a casualty of war,
not a crime.

1334
02:03:46,753 --> 02:03:52,464
And, in all this, the man with the star
was only one against many.

1335
02:03:52,882 --> 02:03:55,675
But time was running out
for the reckless ones...

1336
02:03:55,842 --> 02:03:59,511
...the desperadoes,
the gallop-and-gunshot boys...

1337
02:03:59,679 --> 02:04:02,471
...as more and more citizens demanded
respect for the law...

1338
02:04:02,639 --> 02:04:05,515
...and showed themselves ready to fight
to uphold it.

1339
02:04:05,683 --> 02:04:09,017
And the raw mew towns that sprung up
in the West began to dream...

1340
02:04:09,185 --> 02:04:13,938
...of becoming as refined as that one-time
hooligan city by the Golden Gate.

1341
02:04:14,106 --> 02:04:16,398
San Francisco was now respectable.

1342
02:04:16,565 --> 02:04:20,526
So sophisticated, in fact,
it even had mansions up for auction.

1343
02:04:20,694 --> 02:04:22,360
MAN:
Two thousand dollars.

1344
02:04:22,528 --> 02:04:24,529
Two thousand dollars.

1345
02:04:24,697 --> 02:04:26,780
Is that your last bid?

1346
02:04:26,948 --> 02:04:31,534
Ladies and gentlemen. this trophy
is solid gold and fully inscribed.

1347
02:04:31,702 --> 02:04:36,662
"Mr. Cleve Van Valen, president.
San Francisco-Kansas City Railroad."

1348
02:04:36,830 --> 02:04:39,580
It's a treasure he held dear to his heart.

1349
02:04:39,748 --> 02:04:43,667
Do I hear $3000
for this priceless possession?

1350
02:04:43,835 --> 02:04:46,210
Priceless, my foot.

1351
02:04:46,378 --> 02:04:48,713
We used it for a doorstop.

1352
02:04:49,213 --> 02:04:51,715
Twenty-five hundred.
Twenty-five hundred dollars.

1353
02:04:51,882 --> 02:04:53,716
Twenty-five hundred dollars.

1354
02:04:53,883 --> 02:04:56,551
Twenty-five hundred? Sold $2500.

1355
02:04:57,261 --> 02:04:59,386
It's a sad day, Lilith.

1356
02:04:59,554 --> 02:05:01,054
Sad?

1357
02:05:01,222 --> 02:05:03,889
We made and spent
three fortunes together.

1358
02:05:04,057 --> 02:05:06,058
What's so sad about that?

1359
02:05:06,225 --> 02:05:09,893
And if he'd lived a little longer,
we would've made and spent another.

1360
02:05:10,186 --> 02:05:12,313
I beg your pardon, Mrs. Van Valen.
What?

1361
02:05:12,480 --> 02:05:14,439
The chair, it's been sold. I'm sorry.

1362
02:05:14,606 --> 02:05:17,274
Well then. take it.
Quit apologizing and take it.

1363
02:05:17,442 --> 02:05:18,692
Thank you, madam.

1364
02:05:18,860 --> 02:05:21,402
If there'd been some other way
to pay off the debts...

1365
02:05:21,570 --> 02:05:22,862
It doesn't matter.

1366
02:05:23,030 --> 02:05:26,489
I've got two things
no one can ever take from me:

1367
02:05:27,157 --> 02:05:30,700
This and my land in Arizona.

1368
02:05:30,868 --> 02:05:33,827
Lilith, I don't want to dash any hopes...

1369
02:05:33,995 --> 02:05:36,204
...but that ranch is nearly worthless.

1370
02:05:36,372 --> 02:05:37,872
Well, it's there, isn't it?

1371
02:05:38,040 --> 02:05:40,915
Yes. but most of the cattle
have been sold off or stolen.

1372
02:05:41,083 --> 02:05:43,585
I'll get cattle.
You'll meed someone to work it.

1373
02:05:43,753 --> 02:05:46,086
Someone to manage it for you.
I'll get that too.

1374
02:05:46,254 --> 02:05:47,378
Who?

1375
02:05:47,546 --> 02:05:51,590
My nephew.
He's a marshal out there somewhere.

1376
02:05:51,758 --> 02:05:55,509
Now, Lilith. at your age,
it might be kind of rough.

1377
02:05:56,094 --> 02:05:57,678
Rough?

1378
02:05:57,845 --> 02:06:02,639
My ma and pa were killed
going down the river just looking for land.

1379
02:06:03,224 --> 02:06:07,435
I guess I got a little of that
Prescott blood in me after all.

1380
02:06:16,317 --> 02:06:17,359
Pa?

1381
02:06:17,943 --> 02:06:21,944
Is Aunt Lilith's house on Nob Hill
as high as that?

1382
02:06:23,280 --> 02:06:24,822
I don't know. son.

1383
02:06:24,990 --> 02:06:28,824
On our way home. you ask your aunt Lilith.
She'll tell you.

1384
02:07:17,568 --> 02:07:20,153
Homey? Do you think you'll know her?

1385
02:07:20,320 --> 02:07:21,821
What?
You aunt Lilith.

1386
02:07:21,988 --> 02:07:24,656
Do you think you'll recognize her?
Sure.

1387
02:07:24,824 --> 02:07:28,158
Zeb? What's the matter?

1388
02:07:28,535 --> 02:07:29,827
Nothing.

1389
02:07:29,994 --> 02:07:31,494
Come on.

1390
02:07:37,208 --> 02:07:38,999
Thank you.

1391
02:07:44,295 --> 02:07:48,339
Ma'am, are you our great-aunt Lilith?
If you're Zeb's children, I an.

1392
02:07:51,300 --> 02:07:53,969
Lilith.
Zeb.

1393
02:07:55,011 --> 02:07:57,513
Zeb Rawlings.

1394
02:07:57,681 --> 02:07:59,180
Oh, goodness.

1395
02:07:59,348 --> 02:08:02,182
I swore up and down I wasn't gonna cry.

1396
02:08:02,517 --> 02:08:05,893
You're just as pretty as Ma said you was.

1397
02:08:06,061 --> 02:08:08,312
I'd like you to meet my wife, Julie.

1398
02:08:08,479 --> 02:08:09,896
Pleased to meet you.

1399
02:08:10,064 --> 02:08:12,314
I'm pleased to meet you too.

1400
02:08:12,482 --> 02:08:15,692
I just can't tell you how pleased.

1401
02:08:15,860 --> 02:08:18,694
This here's Eve. underneath all the jam.

1402
02:08:18,862 --> 02:08:21,029
Come on and meet San now.
Sam?

1403
02:08:21,197 --> 02:08:24,699
San's our horse.
He could pull two wagons if he wanted.

1404
02:08:24,867 --> 02:08:28,660
Oh, well, if you'll excuse me,
I have my orders to meet San.

1405
02:08:28,828 --> 02:08:29,869
Come on.

1406
02:08:30,370 --> 02:08:33,121
Oh, just a minute now, boys.
But he's on the other side.

1407
02:08:33,289 --> 02:08:34,747
LINUS: Come on.
PRESCOTT: Okay.

1408
02:08:34,915 --> 02:08:36,290
LINUS: Come on.
LILITH: Just a minute.

1409
02:08:36,458 --> 02:08:38,667
I think this means a whole lot to her.

1410
02:08:38,835 --> 02:08:41,294
You have no idea how much
it means to me...

1411
02:08:41,462 --> 02:08:45,380
...to be able to settle down
to a life of peace and quiet.

1412
02:08:45,548 --> 02:08:46,964
I'll get the luggage.

1413
02:08:48,091 --> 02:08:50,091
(MAN CACKLING)

1414
02:08:50,259 --> 02:08:52,302
MAN:
Hello, boys.

1415
02:08:52,470 --> 02:08:54,219
Jake.

1416
02:08:54,554 --> 02:08:55,637
Ton.

1417
02:08:55,805 --> 02:08:57,513
Pablo.

1418
02:09:07,730 --> 02:09:10,148
Zeb. Let's go.

1419
02:09:10,315 --> 02:09:16,402
Now, marshal, don't tell me you come
all the way to Gold City just to meet me?

1420
02:09:16,570 --> 02:09:19,154
I hardly expected it.

1421
02:09:19,572 --> 02:09:23,532
And the beautiful, Mrs. Rawlings?

1422
02:09:23,700 --> 02:09:25,658
What a pleasure.

1423
02:09:25,826 --> 02:09:30,162
I envy you, marshal.
A well-favored, bright-eyed wife...

1424
02:09:30,330 --> 02:09:34,165
...just as dazzling as that sun up there.

1425
02:09:35,082 --> 02:09:37,501
Makes you almost thankful, don't it?

1426
02:09:37,668 --> 02:09:40,336
It makes a person wanna live.

1427
02:09:41,129 --> 02:09:43,129
(SPEAKS IN SPANISH)

1428
02:09:46,674 --> 02:09:48,257
That's Charlie Gant.

1429
02:09:48,425 --> 02:09:50,801
I thought you said he was in Montana.

1430
02:09:50,969 --> 02:09:52,636
Zeb?

1431
02:09:52,803 --> 02:09:55,596
I'm just gonna get the luggage, that's all.

1432
02:10:04,687 --> 02:10:06,270
See to the rooms, will you, Julie?

1433
02:10:06,438 --> 02:10:09,064
Prescott. take care of the horses.
Yes, sir.

1434
02:10:09,232 --> 02:10:12,650
Linus, help your mother.
Yes, sir.

1435
02:10:18,948 --> 02:10:20,989
Anything wrong, Julie?

1436
02:10:21,157 --> 02:10:23,824
No. No. nothing.

1437
02:10:23,992 --> 02:10:26,117
Come on. Eve.

1438
02:10:32,457 --> 02:10:34,958
Lou.
Zeb.

1439
02:10:35,125 --> 02:10:36,625
Got a minute?

1440
02:10:36,793 --> 02:10:38,794
Of course I got a minute.

1441
02:10:40,587 --> 02:10:42,088
Here.

1442
02:10:42,256 --> 02:10:44,798
MAN: Now, I urge you,
most respectfully to peruse the...

1443
02:10:44,966 --> 02:10:47,591
Cigar?
No, thanks.

1444
02:10:47,968 --> 02:10:50,301
Well, what can I do for you?

1445
02:10:51,804 --> 02:10:53,137
Go ahead, name it.

1446
02:10:53,305 --> 02:10:56,139
I saw Gant get off the train this morning.

1447
02:10:56,307 --> 02:10:58,849
There were three men waiting for him.

1448
02:11:01,936 --> 02:11:04,395
That's why you're here, huh?

1449
02:11:04,896 --> 02:11:06,772
That's it.

1450
02:11:08,774 --> 02:11:11,149
Look. there ain't a thing we can do...

1451
02:11:11,317 --> 02:11:15,903
...to keep Charlie Gant from going
where he wants to in this territory.

1452
02:11:16,697 --> 02:11:20,407
I know. I know what he was...

1453
02:11:20,658 --> 02:11:22,825
...but that's over now.

1454
02:11:23,285 --> 02:11:25,702
It was over the day his brother got...

1455
02:11:27,621 --> 02:11:30,664
Should've killed then both
that day, but...

1456
02:11:31,164 --> 02:11:34,375
Well, you didn't.
There ain't a thing I can do about it now.

1457
02:11:34,543 --> 02:11:37,294
What's he doing here, Lou?
Ain't you even curious?

1458
02:11:37,461 --> 02:11:40,963
Well, what do you want me to do?
Run him out of town at the point of a gun?

1459
02:11:41,131 --> 02:11:43,673
Do you think we still put the law
inside a holster here?

1460
02:11:43,841 --> 02:11:46,925
Look over there, Zeb. There's the law.

1461
02:11:47,093 --> 02:11:50,344
With all its writs and decrees and...

1462
02:11:50,846 --> 02:11:54,514
We abide by that circuit judge now.
How many get killed meantime?

1463
02:11:54,682 --> 02:11:56,599
Nobody's got killed. Nobody's going to.

1464
02:11:56,766 --> 02:12:00,018
Doc Holliday, the Clantons,
the Youngers...

1465
02:12:00,477 --> 02:12:04,521
They're all gone now.
Charlie Gant ain't gone.

1466
02:12:05,481 --> 02:12:08,482
You get me a warrant. I'll get you Gant.

1467
02:12:08,734 --> 02:12:12,568
Lou? They want three guards in the wagon
with the gold shipment tomorrow.

1468
02:12:12,736 --> 02:12:17,363
Three?
This is a big one. Over $100,000 worth.

1469
02:12:17,531 --> 02:12:20,449
I'll take Clayton and Sims with me,
all right?

1470
02:12:24,953 --> 02:12:26,453
Well?

1471
02:12:26,621 --> 02:12:28,496
Well what?

1472
02:12:28,706 --> 02:12:30,831
Doesn't that mean anything to you?

1473
02:12:30,999 --> 02:12:34,375
It means we put on a three-nan guard.
To the train.

1474
02:12:34,543 --> 02:12:36,710
What happens then?

1475
02:12:36,878 --> 02:12:39,463
You know there's gold going out here
every month or so.

1476
02:12:39,631 --> 02:12:43,257
There hasn't been a train robbery
since Jesse James was killed.

1477
02:12:44,216 --> 02:12:47,217
MAN: Now, if the councilors
wish to have a conference, we'll have one.

1478
02:12:47,385 --> 02:12:48,886
Zeb.

1479
02:12:50,346 --> 02:12:54,306
I don't want any trouble here now.
We've been friends a long time.

1480
02:12:55,016 --> 02:12:57,100
As a friend...

1481
02:12:57,267 --> 02:12:59,310
...I'd like you to leave town.

1482
02:13:21,451 --> 02:13:23,744
Boys, get back from there.

1483
02:13:26,664 --> 02:13:28,413
Look down there. son.

1484
02:13:28,581 --> 02:13:31,124
Do you know how deep that shaft is?
Uh-uh.

1485
02:13:31,292 --> 02:13:33,167
That's a thousand foot deep.

1486
02:13:33,335 --> 02:13:34,919
Do you know how deep
a thousand foot is?

1487
02:13:35,086 --> 02:13:36,086
Uh-uh.

1488
02:13:36,253 --> 02:13:40,422
Well, if you had 200 brothers,
all standing on your shoulders...

1489
02:13:40,590 --> 02:13:44,592
...you wouldn't be able to see
over the top. I'd be squished.

1490
02:13:44,760 --> 02:13:48,345
Come on.
I'll show you boys the donkey engine.

1491
02:13:53,599 --> 02:13:56,892
You boys go ahead.
I'll be along in a minute.

1492
02:13:59,603 --> 02:14:03,105
I hear you've been talking
to the local marshal about me.

1493
02:14:04,941 --> 02:14:09,068
Would you call that friendly?
I never considered us exactly friendly.

1494
02:14:09,485 --> 02:14:11,653
I don't like you, marshal.

1495
02:14:11,821 --> 02:14:15,698
I don't like what you and your kind
are doing to this country.

1496
02:14:16,198 --> 02:14:18,074
Now, I don't want any trouble.

1497
02:14:18,242 --> 02:14:22,744
But you wanna put things on the old basis,
just you and me?

1498
02:14:22,912 --> 02:14:25,246
That's fine.

1499
02:14:25,414 --> 02:14:28,456
I'm not gonna
get in a fight with you, Gant.

1500
02:14:29,291 --> 02:14:31,875
It's peace you want. huh, marshal?

1501
02:14:32,043 --> 02:14:33,459
Peace?

1502
02:14:33,627 --> 02:14:36,462
There's only one kind I know of.

1503
02:14:37,171 --> 02:14:39,339
That's the kind my brother's got.

1504
02:14:39,590 --> 02:14:43,300
What happened to your brother
didn't teach you very much, did it?

1505
02:14:43,468 --> 02:14:45,802
Easy, marshal.

1506
02:14:46,095 --> 02:14:47,803
Floyd never made mistakes...

1507
02:14:47,971 --> 02:14:51,180
...except the one time he trusted you.

1508
02:14:51,348 --> 02:14:53,224
And you're the one that got away.

1509
02:14:57,019 --> 02:15:00,271
One of these days, I'm likely
to pay you Rawlingses a little visit.

1510
02:15:07,360 --> 02:15:09,318
(IMITATES GUNSHOTS)

1511
02:15:12,155 --> 02:15:14,156
(GANT CACKLING)

1512
02:15:27,374 --> 02:15:29,583
MAN 1:
Come on. move along.

1513
02:15:29,751 --> 02:15:32,084
Get those gold boxes up there.

1514
02:15:32,252 --> 02:15:34,378
MAN 2:
That's a lot of gold.

1515
02:15:34,546 --> 02:15:37,130
MAN 1:
Come on. keep moving, boys.

1516
02:15:39,507 --> 02:15:40,841
Zeb?

1517
02:15:41,009 --> 02:15:43,301
Lou Ramsey's here.

1518
02:15:45,220 --> 02:15:46,845
Lou.

1519
02:15:47,472 --> 02:15:50,306
I warmed you, Zeb.
What is it?

1520
02:15:50,474 --> 02:15:52,766
Gant came to see me last night.

1521
02:15:52,933 --> 02:15:55,893
Said you tried to start
some trouble with him.

1522
02:15:56,060 --> 02:15:57,644
You believe him?

1523
02:15:57,812 --> 02:16:01,063
I'm telling you, Zeb, you take your
trouble to your own territory.

1524
02:16:01,231 --> 02:16:02,773
I don't want any more of it here.

1525
02:16:06,027 --> 02:16:09,694
There won't be any more trouble. Lou.
Gant's gone.

1526
02:16:09,862 --> 02:16:12,322
Rode out of here early this morning.

1527
02:16:12,615 --> 02:16:13,697
With who?

1528
02:16:13,865 --> 02:16:15,699
ZEB:
His gang.

1529
02:16:16,201 --> 02:16:20,660
They should be somewhere
between here and Kingman...

1530
02:16:20,828 --> 02:16:22,037
...waiting on that train.

1531
02:16:22,538 --> 02:16:24,288
You don't fool me for a minute, Zeb.

1532
02:16:24,456 --> 02:16:27,165
You are not looking for a robbery,
you're looking for Gant.

1533
02:16:27,333 --> 02:16:30,542
You still carry lead where he shot you.
That was Texas.

1534
02:16:30,710 --> 02:16:34,045
And Oklahoma, where you killed Floyd.
And now this.

1535
02:16:36,256 --> 02:16:38,298
I'm sorry, Julie...

1536
02:16:38,466 --> 02:16:42,009
...but I don't want my office
to be any part of this.

1537
02:16:51,850 --> 02:16:52,892
Zeb?

1538
02:16:53,060 --> 02:16:55,519
The boys have got the team hitched.

1539
02:16:56,020 --> 02:16:57,437
ZEB:
I know.

1540
02:16:57,605 --> 02:16:59,772
It's almost time to go.

1541
02:17:03,818 --> 02:17:05,567
Zeb?

1542
02:17:29,418 --> 02:17:32,336
Julie.
No one's asking you to face Gant.

1543
02:17:32,504 --> 02:17:34,255
No one's making you.

1544
02:17:34,422 --> 02:17:37,507
We could ride out of here right now.
We could forget it.

1545
02:17:41,261 --> 02:17:44,720
Maybe there's
something you haven't told me.

1546
02:17:45,222 --> 02:17:47,097
Is there. Zeb?

1547
02:17:51,101 --> 02:17:54,018
I'm asking you not to go.

1548
02:17:54,687 --> 02:17:56,436
Please.

1549
02:17:56,771 --> 02:17:59,189
Don't go.

1550
02:18:00,357 --> 02:18:01,691
Sorry, Julie.

1551
02:18:19,454 --> 02:18:25,291
I guess there's nothing more pigheaded
in a nan than his sense of honor.

1552
02:18:25,458 --> 02:18:29,210
They're all the same, every one of then.

1553
02:18:29,378 --> 02:18:31,461
You take my Cleve now.

1554
02:18:31,629 --> 02:18:34,088
Never could turn down a poker game.

1555
02:18:34,256 --> 02:18:36,382
Felt duty-bound to go.

1556
02:18:36,550 --> 02:18:39,092
Three nights running sometimes,
but he wouldn't quit...

1557
02:18:39,260 --> 02:18:42,344
...not if his life depended on it. He...

1558
02:18:43,847 --> 02:18:45,722
I guess it isn't very funny.

1559
02:18:45,890 --> 02:18:47,515
PRESCOTT:
Ma?

1560
02:18:47,891 --> 02:18:48,932
Where's Pa?

1561
02:18:49,100 --> 02:18:51,601
LILITH: Out. That's where he is.
What's the matter with Mon?

1562
02:18:51,768 --> 02:18:54,562
Nothing's the matter.
Come on. now, in the other room.

1563
02:18:54,729 --> 02:18:56,855
What's the matter?
LILITH: Come on, we're gonna play.

1564
02:18:57,023 --> 02:18:58,647
That's a good girl. That's better.

1565
02:18:58,815 --> 02:19:01,317
LINUS: What's the matter with Mama?
Nothing's the matter.

1566
02:19:01,484 --> 02:19:02,609
Do you know any games?

1567
02:19:02,776 --> 02:19:04,694
PRESCOTT: We know tag.
LINUS: Musical chairs.

1568
02:19:04,862 --> 02:19:06,612
Ugh. Tag.
I know hide-and-seek.

1569
02:19:06,779 --> 02:19:08,487
Well, do you know how to play poker?

1570
02:19:08,655 --> 02:19:09,655
Poker?
Poker?

1571
02:19:09,823 --> 02:19:13,533
You're in luck. Sit down right there.
Now, come on, sit down. That's it.

1572
02:19:13,784 --> 02:19:15,576
But we don't know how to play poker.

1573
02:19:15,744 --> 02:19:18,078
Well, it's time you learned.

1574
02:19:18,246 --> 02:19:21,915
First, we'll start off
with a little five-card stud.

1575
02:19:40,345 --> 02:19:42,512
I'll take that rifle, Zeb.

1576
02:19:42,680 --> 02:19:43,846
Your pistol too.

1577
02:19:47,183 --> 02:19:49,059
Sorry, Lou.

1578
02:19:49,435 --> 02:19:50,809
I just can't oblige.

1579
02:20:00,317 --> 02:20:02,652
Thought the law wouldn't let you
use that anymore.

1580
02:20:03,736 --> 02:20:05,362
I'll use it if I have to.

1581
02:20:05,947 --> 02:20:09,198
I'm going out of here. Lou,
and I'm taking this with me.

1582
02:20:09,699 --> 02:20:11,199
To kill Gant.

1583
02:20:11,367 --> 02:20:13,326
That's what you think, isn't it?

1584
02:20:13,494 --> 02:20:16,203
It's something personal
between him and me.

1585
02:20:16,371 --> 02:20:18,704
Well, Lou. it could be...

1586
02:20:18,872 --> 02:20:22,290
...if I settle down with my family
and wait for him to come.

1587
02:20:22,458 --> 02:20:26,001
And he'll come
if I don't stop him here and now.

1588
02:20:26,169 --> 02:20:29,712
I'm gonna catch Gant red-handed,
breaking the law...

1589
02:20:29,880 --> 02:20:33,715
...and then I'm gonna use the law
to put him away once and for all.

1590
02:20:33,883 --> 02:20:35,132
The law, Lou.

1591
02:20:35,592 --> 02:20:37,385
I'm gonna use the law...

1592
02:20:37,552 --> 02:20:40,428
...but I haven't got much chance
without your help.

1593
02:21:05,905 --> 02:21:07,531
How many men in the caboose?

1594
02:21:07,699 --> 02:21:09,073
Just one brakeman.

1595
02:21:09,241 --> 02:21:12,534
Is he armed?
No, never has been.

1596
02:21:12,702 --> 02:21:14,911
I'll be in the express car.

1597
02:21:20,624 --> 02:21:21,916
Thanks, Lou.

1598
02:21:22,084 --> 02:21:25,918
Marshal?
There's some riders up ahead.

1599
02:21:26,753 --> 02:21:29,088
ZEB:
I'll take a look.

1600
02:21:48,978 --> 02:21:51,520
Engineer. there's a barricade ahead!

1601
02:21:51,688 --> 02:21:53,438
Open it up, wide open.

1602
02:22:19,499 --> 02:22:20,957
Zeb!

1603
02:22:21,125 --> 02:22:24,127
Come on. Come on.

1604
02:22:44,017 --> 02:22:45,975
GANT: Everyone make it?
Frenchy's horse fell.

1605
02:22:46,143 --> 02:22:48,186
I don't think he made it.
Well, let's move.

1606
02:22:48,353 --> 02:22:50,312
It's a long way from here to that gold.

1607
02:22:50,480 --> 02:22:52,313
There's no danger. Just keep going.

1608
02:23:10,660 --> 02:23:12,660
It's Rawlings.

1609
02:24:11,620 --> 02:24:13,287
(YELLS)

1610
02:24:43,476 --> 02:24:45,060
Back this train up!

1611
02:24:45,228 --> 02:24:46,435
And fast!

1612
02:24:46,603 --> 02:24:48,187
(GANT CACKLES)

1613
02:27:13,374 --> 02:27:15,166
How come we're leaving so early, Pa?

1614
02:27:15,334 --> 02:27:18,085
ZEB:
We got a long way to go, son.

1615
02:27:18,253 --> 02:27:19,836
Here.

1616
02:27:23,423 --> 02:27:25,590
Auntie, when we going to your house?

1617
02:27:25,758 --> 02:27:27,967
Your daddy will decide
when we get to your home.

1618
02:27:28,134 --> 02:27:29,677
Auntie, can we take San with us?

1619
02:27:29,844 --> 02:27:32,679
I think Sam is taking us.

1620
02:27:54,403 --> 02:27:57,029
Pa, how much further is it
to Aunt Lilith's ranch?

1621
02:27:57,197 --> 02:28:00,573
Well, son, it's around the next bend,
the next bend...

1622
02:28:00,741 --> 02:28:03,200
...and the valley beyond.
Oh.

1623
02:28:03,576 --> 02:28:06,119
(HUMMING "HOME lN THE MEADOW")

1624
02:28:06,287 --> 02:28:09,788
Aunt Lilith. do you know that song?
LINUS: That's our song.

1625
02:28:09,956 --> 02:28:11,373
Your song?

1626
02:28:11,541 --> 02:28:15,625
I sang that song
long before your pa was ever born.

1627
02:28:16,043 --> 02:28:18,502
(SINGING "HOME lN THE MEADOW")

1628
02:28:20,130 --> 02:28:21,130
Come on.

1629
02:28:27,260 --> 02:28:28,884
Zeb.

1630
02:29:02,744 --> 02:29:09,247
The West that was won by its pioneers,
settlers, adventurers is long gone now.

1631
02:29:09,415 --> 02:29:11,874
Yet it is theirs forever.

1632
02:29:12,042 --> 02:29:16,627
For they left tracks in history that
will never be eroded by wind or rain...

1633
02:29:16,795 --> 02:29:22,465
...mever plowed under by tractors,
never buried in the compost of events.

1634
02:29:23,050 --> 02:29:26,760
Out of the hard simplicity of their lives,
out of their vitality...

1635
02:29:26,927 --> 02:29:29,428
...their hopes and their sorrows...

1636
02:29:29,596 --> 02:29:31,596
...grew legends of courage and pride...

1637
02:29:31,764 --> 02:29:35,599
...to inspire their children
and their children's children.

1638
02:29:36,267 --> 02:29:38,684
From soil enriched by their blood...

1639
02:29:38,852 --> 02:29:41,644
...out of their fever
to explore and build...

1640
02:29:41,812 --> 02:29:45,105
...came lakes where once
were burning deserts...

1641
02:29:45,357 --> 02:29:48,775
...came the goods of the earth,
mimes and wheat fields...

1642
02:29:48,942 --> 02:29:51,401
...orchards and great lumber mills...

1643
02:29:51,569 --> 02:29:54,904
...all the sinews of a growing country.

1644
02:29:56,156 --> 02:30:00,116
Out of their rude settlements,
their trading posts, came cities...

1645
02:30:00,284 --> 02:30:03,285
...to rank among the great ones
of the world.

1646
02:30:03,453 --> 02:30:06,579
All the heritage of a people
free to dream...

1647
02:30:06,747 --> 02:30:11,291
...free to act,
free to mold their own destiny.
